{"title_page": "Lifeblood, the Thrombosis Charity", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Lifeblood (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox non-profit\n| name = Thrombosis UK\n| caption = Example logo\n| founder = [[Beverley Hunt]], Alan Moody\n| registration_id = 1090540\n| founded_date = 2002\n| area_served = [[United Kingdom]]\n| services = Charitable services\n| focus = Prevention of [[venous thromboembolism]]\n| homepage = {{URL|thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php}}\n}}\n\nThrombosis UK, (previously known as 'Lifeblood, the Thrombosis Charity' is a [[UK]] based charity whose stated mission is to increase awareness of [[thrombosis]] among the public and health professionals, and to raise research funds to improve patient care through improved prevention and treatment of venous thromboembolic disease. \n\nThe charity is governed by nine trustees and is supported by a multi-disciplinary group. Along with efforts to support research in thrombosis and to raise awareness through an annual \"National Thrombosis Week\", they campaign for governments in the UK to prioritise [[venous thromboembolism]] (VTE) prevention in the [[National Health Service]] ('Stop the Clots'). They also strive to improve the clinical diagnosis of venous thromboembolism in the community ('Spot the Clots').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2005-06/373 |title=Early day motion 373 \u2013 Preventing deaths from thrombosis |publisher=UK Parliament|date=20 June 2005|last=Smith |first= John P |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/4120905.htm |title=Memorandum by Lifeblood: the Thrombosis Charity (VT 6) \u2013 House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Minutes of Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=11 March 2005 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThrombosis UK was founded in 2002 by Professor [[Beverley Hunt]], Consultant Haematologist at [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust]] and Professor Alan Moody, Professor of Radiology at the [[University of Nottingham]] to address two important issues: improving medical and general knowledge of thrombosis, and raising funds for research into thrombosis.<ref name=\"hunt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=66&Itemid=67|title=Why Lifeblood: The Thrombosis Charity was founded|author=Beverley J. Hunt|publisher=Lifeblood, the Thrombosis Charity|accessdate=4 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618031323/http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=66&Itemid=67|archivedate=18 June 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, the charity started campaigning to raise awareness. They founded the yearly National Thrombosis Week and provided evidence on [[#Parliamentary testimony|several health select committees]].<ref name=\"NTW\" /> They also won the title of 'Health Charity of the Year' in 2010.<ref name=\"charityawards\" /> In the same year, Lifeblood published the results of a conducted survey which showed that there is a big education gap concerning hospital acquired blood clots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/health/patients-in-dark-over-blood-clots-14765267.html?r%3DRSS |title=Patients in dark over blood clots \u2013 Health, News | publisher=Belfasttelegraph.co.uk |date=13 April 2010 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> \n\nIn 2010, on behalf of Lifeblood, Professor Hunt was included as a member of the guideline development group for the [[National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence]] (NICE) guidelines in which mandatory thrombosis risk assessment of all patients on admission was set as a must for all [[National Health Service]] (NHS) hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/7079067/All-hospital-patients-to-be-checked-for-risk-of-potentially-fatal-blood-clot.html |title=All hospital patients 'to be checked for risk of potentially fatal blood clot' |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> In 2011, Lifeblood continued political campaigning with the All Parliamentary Thrombosis Group and health professionals which led to the CQUIN VTE targets which mandate VTE risk assessment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8504015/Failure-to-spot-blood-clots-costs-the-NHS-millions.html |title=Failure to spot blood clots costs the NHS millions |publisher=Telegraph |date=10 May 2011 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-13333749|title=NHS 'failure' to spot blood clots costing millions |author=Roberts, Michelle |date=10 May 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n\n=== Stop the Clots ===\nThe 'Stop the Clots' campaign aims to ensure that every adult patient admitted to hospital across the UK receives a venous thromboembolism risk assessment and appropriate prophylaxis in line with national clinical guidelines (SIGN Clinical Guideline in [[Scotland]], and NICE Clinical Guideline 92 in [[England]], [[Wales]] and [[Northern Ireland]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iow.nhs.uk/index.asp?record=1485 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130125324/http://www.iow.nhs.uk/index.asp?record=1485 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-11-30 |title=Lifeblood \u2013 The Thrombosis Charity |publisher=NHS, Isle of Wight |accessdate=2012-08-06 }}</ref>\nThe House of Commons welcomed the parliamentary launch of Lifeblood: The Thrombosis Charity and commended its campaign to Stop the Clots in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2003-04/304 |title=Early day motion 304 \u2013 LIFEBLOOD: THE THROMBOSIS CHARITY |publisher=UK Parliament|date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Spot the Clots ===\nThe 'Spot the Clots' campaign is aimed at the community, hoping to improve education of health professionals and raise awareness of the general public about blood clots.<ref name=\"rcn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rcn.org.uk/development/practice/patient_safety/vte|title=Venous thromboembolism|publisher=Royal College of Nursing|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"lifeblood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1&Itemid=28 |title=Mission Statement |publisher=Lifeblood, the Thrombosis Charity |accessdate=4 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618032316/http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1&Itemid=28 |archivedate=18 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== National Thrombosis Week ===\nNational Thrombosis Week is an annual awareness-raising campaign run by Lifeblood every spring. Campaigns were lauded by Parliament in 2006 and 2008.<ref name=\"NTW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2005-06/2091 |title=Early day motion 2091 \u2013 NATIONAL THROMBOSIS WEEK 2006 |publisher=UK Parliament|date=3 April 2006 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2007-08/1566 |title=Early day motion 1566 \u2013 NATIONAL THROMBOSIS WEEK |publisher=UK Parliament|date=14 May 2008 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n\n== Parliamentary testimony ==\n\nLifeblood provided both written and oral evidence on several Health Committees:\n\n*In December 2004 Lifeblood gave oral evidence before the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] Health Committee about the importance of prevention of venous thromboembolism and the importance of the use of [[thromboprophylaxis]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/4120901.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Minutes of Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In February 2005 Lifeblood gave written evidence at the House of Commons [[Health Select Committee]]'s Second report on [[venous thromboembolism]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/9912.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Second Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/9902.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Second Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In March 2007 Lifeblood provided written evidence as a response to the House of Commons Health Select Committee's Inquiry into NICE.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmselect/cmhealth/503/503we41.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Written Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=17 May 2007 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In October 2007 Professor Beverley Hunt represented Lifeblood in the House of Commons and gave oral evidence during the Fifth Evidence Session in inquiry into NICE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmselect/cmhealth/cmhealth.htm |title=The House of Commons \u2013 Health Reports |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref>\n*In October 2008 Lifeblood provided written evidence for the House of Commons Health Select Committee's Inquiry into [[Patient Safety]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmselect/cmhealth/1137/1137we01.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Written Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=30 October 2008 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In November 2010 Lifeblood gave written evidence for the House of Commons Health Select Committee's Inquiry into the revalidation of doctors.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmhealth/557/557vw25.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health Committee \u2013 Written Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In May 2012 Lifeblood provided a submission to the [[National Assembly for Wales]] Health and Social Committee inquiry into [[venous thromboembolism]] prevention in [[Wales]].<ref>[http://www.senedd.assemblywales.org/documents/s7733/Consultation%20response%20VTE%208%20-%20Dr%20Simon%20Noble.pdf \"Consultation response VTE \u2013 Dr. Simon Noble\"] Wales Assembly. (PDF).</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nIn November 2007 the House of Commons congratulated Lifeblood in an [[early day motion]] for its work during the previous five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2007-08/413 |title=Early day motion 413 \u2013 LIFEBLOOD THROMBOSIS CHARITY \u2013 UK Parliament |last=Smith |first=John P |publisher=Parliament.uk |date=27 November 2007 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> Lifeblood was also the winner of the Charity Awards 2010 in the category for Healthcare and Medical Research.<ref name=\"charityawards\">{{cite web |url=http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/charityawards |title=Awards |publisher=Civil Society |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807101432/http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/charityawards |archive-date=7 August 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120423065152/http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php Official Home Page]\n\n[[Category:Health charities in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Lifeblood (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox non-profit\n| name = Thrombosis UK\n| caption = Example logo\n| founder = [[Beverley Hunt]], Alan Moody\n| registration_id = 1090540\n| founded_date = 2002\n| area_served = [[United Kingdom]]\n| services = Charitable services\n| focus = Prevention of [[venous thromboembolism]]\n| homepage = {{URL|thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php}}\n}}\n\nThrombosis UK, (previously known as 'Lifeblood, the Thrombosis Charity' is a [[UK]] based charity whose stated mission is to increase awareness of [[thrombosis]] among the public and health professionals, and to raise research funds to improve patient care through improved prevention and treatment of venous thromboembolic disease. The charity is governed by nine trustees and is supported by a multi-disciplinary group. Along with efforts to support research in thrombosis and to raise awareness through an annual \"National Thrombosis Week\", they campaign for governments in the UK to prioritise [[venous thromboembolism]] (VTE) prevention in the [[National Health Service]] ('Stop the Clots'). They also strive to improve the clinical diagnosis of venous thromboembolism in the community ('Spot the Clots').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2005-06/373 |title=Early day motion 373 \u2013 Preventing deaths from thrombosis |publisher=UK Parliament|date=20 June 2005|last=Smith |first= John P |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/4120905.htm |title=Memorandum by Lifeblood: the Thrombosis Charity (VT 6) \u2013 House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Minutes of Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=11 March 2005 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThrombosis UK was founded in 2002 by Professor [[Beverley Hunt]], Consultant Haematologist at [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust]] and Professor Alan Moody, Professor of Radiology at the [[University of Nottingham]] to address two important issues: improving medical and general knowledge of thrombosis, and raising funds for research into thrombosis.<ref name=\"hunt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=66&Itemid=67|title=Why Lifeblood: The Thrombosis Charity was founded|author=Beverley J. Hunt|publisher=Lifeblood, the Thrombosis Charity|accessdate=4 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618031323/http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=66&Itemid=67|archivedate=18 June 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2003, the charity started campaigning to raise awareness. They founded the yearly National Thrombosis Week and provided evidence on [[#Parliamentary testimony|several health select committees]].<ref name=\"NTW\"/> They also won the title of 'Health Charity of the Year' in 2010.<ref name=\"charityawards\"/> In the same year, Lifeblood published the results of a conducted survey which showed that there is a big education gap concerning hospital acquired blood clots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/health/patients-in-dark-over-blood-clots-14765267.html?r%3DRSS |title=Patients in dark over blood clots \u2013 Health, News | publisher=Belfasttelegraph.co.uk |date=13 April 2010 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> In 2010, on behalf of Lifeblood, Professor Hunt was included as a member of the guideline development group for the [[National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence]] (NICE) guidelines in which mandatory thrombosis risk assessment of all patients on admission was set as a must for all [[National Health Service]] (NHS) hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/7079067/All-hospital-patients-to-be-checked-for-risk-of-potentially-fatal-blood-clot.html |title=All hospital patients 'to be checked for risk of potentially fatal blood clot' |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> In 2011, Lifeblood continued political campaigning with the All Parliamentary Thrombosis Group and health professionals which led to the CQUIN VTE targets which mandate VTE risk assessment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8504015/Failure-to-spot-blood-clots-costs-the-NHS-millions.html |title=Failure to spot blood clots costs the NHS millions |publisher=Telegraph |date=10 May 2011 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-13333749|title=NHS 'failure' to spot blood clots costing millions |author=Roberts, Michelle |date=10 May 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n\n=== Stop the Clots ===\nThe 'Stop the Clots' campaign aims to ensure that every adult patient admitted to hospital across the UK receives a venous thromboembolism risk assessment and appropriate prophylaxis in line with national clinical guidelines (SIGN Clinical Guideline in [[Scotland]], and NICE Clinical Guideline 92 in [[England]], [[Wales]] and [[Northern Ireland]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iow.nhs.uk/index.asp?record=1485 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130125324/http://www.iow.nhs.uk/index.asp?record=1485 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-11-30 |title=Lifeblood \u2013 The Thrombosis Charity |publisher=NHS, Isle of Wight |accessdate=2012-08-06 }}</ref>\nThe House of Commons welcomed the parliamentary launch of Lifeblood: The Thrombosis Charity and commended its campaign to Stop the Clots in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2003-04/304 |title=Early day motion 304 \u2013 LIFEBLOOD: THE THROMBOSIS CHARITY |publisher=UK Parliament|date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Spot the Clots ===\nThe 'Spot the Clots' campaign is aimed at the community, hoping to improve education of health professionals and raise awareness of the general public about blood clots.<ref name=\"rcn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rcn.org.uk/development/practice/patient_safety/vte|title=Venous thromboembolism|publisher=Royal College of Nursing|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"lifeblood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1&Itemid=28 |title=Mission Statement |publisher=Lifeblood, the Thrombosis Charity |accessdate=4 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618032316/http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1&Itemid=28 |archivedate=18 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== National Thrombosis Week ===\nNational Thrombosis Week is an annual awareness-raising campaign run by Lifeblood every spring. Campaigns were lauded by Parliament in 2006 and 2008.<ref name=\"NTW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2005-06/2091 |title=Early day motion 2091 \u2013 NATIONAL THROMBOSIS WEEK 2006 |publisher=UK Parliament|date=3 April 2006 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2007-08/1566 |title=Early day motion 1566 \u2013 NATIONAL THROMBOSIS WEEK |publisher=UK Parliament|date=14 May 2008 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n\n== Parliamentary testimony ==\n\nLifeblood provided both written and oral evidence on several Health Committees:\n\n*In December 2004 Lifeblood gave oral evidence before the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] Health Committee about the importance of prevention of venous thromboembolism and the importance of the use of [[thromboprophylaxis]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/4120901.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Minutes of Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In February 2005 Lifeblood gave written evidence at the House of Commons [[Health Select Committee]]'s Second report on [[venous thromboembolism]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/9912.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Second Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmselect/cmhealth/99/9902.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Second Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In March 2007 Lifeblood provided written evidence as a response to the House of Commons Health Select Committee's Inquiry into NICE.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmselect/cmhealth/503/503we41.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Written Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=17 May 2007 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In October 2007 Professor Beverley Hunt represented Lifeblood in the House of Commons and gave oral evidence during the Fifth Evidence Session in inquiry into NICE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmselect/cmhealth/cmhealth.htm |title=The House of Commons \u2013 Health Reports |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref>\n*In October 2008 Lifeblood provided written evidence for the House of Commons Health Select Committee's Inquiry into [[Patient Safety]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmselect/cmhealth/1137/1137we01.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health \u2013 Written Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=30 October 2008 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In November 2010 Lifeblood gave written evidence for the House of Commons Health Select Committee's Inquiry into the revalidation of doctors.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Committee Office, House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmhealth/557/557vw25.htm |title=House of Commons \u2013 Health Committee \u2013 Written Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>\n*In May 2012 Lifeblood provided a submission to the [[National Assembly for Wales]] Health and Social Committee inquiry into [[venous thromboembolism]] prevention in [[Wales]].<ref>[http://www.senedd.assemblywales.org/documents/s7733/Consultation%20response%20VTE%208%20-%20Dr%20Simon%20Noble.pdf \"Consultation response VTE \u2013 Dr. Simon Noble\"] Wales Assembly. (PDF).</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nIn November 2007 the House of Commons congratulated Lifeblood in an [[early day motion]] for its work during the previous five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2007-08/413 |title=Early day motion 413 \u2013 LIFEBLOOD THROMBOSIS CHARITY \u2013 UK Parliament |last=Smith |first=John P |publisher=Parliament.uk |date=27 November 2007 |accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> Lifeblood was also the winner of the Charity Awards 2010 in the category for Healthcare and Medical Research.<ref name=\"charityawards\">{{cite web |url=http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/charityawards |title=Awards |publisher=Civil Society |date= |accessdate=2012-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807101432/http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/charityawards |archive-date=7 August 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120423065152/http://www.thrombosis-charity.org.uk/cms/index.php Official Home Page]\n\n[[Category:Health charities in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Infogapp1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Space and formatting for easier readability", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lifeblood,_the_Thrombosis_Charity"}
{"title_page": "Sentence spacing studies", "text_new": "'''Sentence spacing studies''' analyse the effects of [[sentence spacing]] techniques on the [[readability]] of text. The only direct [[Observational study|scientific studies]] have been conducted by researchers from the [[University of Georgia]], for on-screen text. There are currently no direct sentence spacing studies for printed text.\n\nThe direct studies, started in 2002, analysed single, double, and triple sentence spacing to determine what was most readable on screen. The researchers concluded that their tests did not show a statistically significant difference between the various techniques, but that further testing was needed.\n\n==Effects on readability and legibility==\nClaims abound regarding the [[Typography#Readability and legibility|legibility]] and [[readability]] of the single and double sentence-spacing methods\u2014by proponents on both sides. However, typographic opinions are typically anecdotal with no basis in evidence.<ref>[[#Whe95|Wheildon 1995]]. p. 13.</ref> According to [[Miles Tinker]], \"Opinions are not always safe guides to legibility of print,\"<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. p. 50.</ref> and when direct studies are conducted, anecdotal opinions\u2014even those of experts\u2014can turn out to be false.<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. pp. 88, 108, 127, 128, 153; [[#Whe95|Wheildon 1995]]. pp. 8, 35.</ref> For example, text that seems readable at first glance may be shown to impair reading effectiveness when subjected to [[Scientific method|scientific study]].<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. pp. 50, 108, 128. A useful example is the Helvetica font, an ubiquitous font that is considered extremely legible (visually pleasing in the construction and viewing of its characters), but has been found to impair reading effectiveness (readability). See [[#Squ06|Squire 2006]]. p. 36.</ref>\n\n=== Direct studies ===\nDirect studies include those by Loh, Branch, Shewanown, & Ali (2002), Clinton, Branch, Holschuh, & Shewanown (2003) and Ni, Branch & Chen (2004) with results favouring neither single, double, nor triple spacing.<ref>[[#Leo03|Leonard et al. 2003]].</ref> The 2002 study indicated that \"the 'double space group' consistently took longer time to finish than the 'single space' group\", but the authors concluded that \"there was not enough evidence to suggest that a significant difference exists\".<ref>[[#Loh02|Loh et al., 2002]]. p. 4. This study used \"on-screen\" text in its analysis.</ref> The 2003 study analysed on-screen single, double, and triple spacing. Again, the authors stated that there was insufficient evidence to draw a conclusion.<ref>[[#Cli03|Clinton 2003.]] The study did not find \"statistically significant differences, between reading time of single and double spaces passages\".</ref> A similar study was conducted in 2009 using identical spacing variables. The authors concluded that the \"results provided insufficient evidence that time and comprehension differ significantly among different conditions of spacing between sentences\".<ref>[[#Bra09|Ni et al. 2009]]. pp. 383, 387, 390. This study \"explored the effects of spacing after the period on on-screen reading tasks through two dependent variables, reading time and reading comprehension\".</ref>\n\n===Related studies===\nThere are other studies that could be relevant to sentence spacing,<ref>[[#Rho99|Rhodes 1999]].</ref> such as the familiarity of typographic conventions on readability. Some studies indicate that \"tradition\" can increase the readability of text,<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. p. 124.</ref> and that reading is disrupted when conventional printing arrangements are disrupted or violated.<ref>[[#Hab81|Haber and Haber 1981]]. pp. 147\u2013148, 152.</ref> The standard for the Web and published books, magazines, and newspapers is single sentence spacing.<ref>[[#Wil03|Williams 2003]]. p. 13.</ref>\n[[Image:The river effect in justified text.jpg|250px|thumb|An example of the \"river\" effect in justified text]]\n\n[[David Jury]]'s book, ''What is Typography?'' notes the following: \"Changes in spacing either between letters and words, or between the words only&nbsp;... do not appear to affect legibility. [These rather extraordinary conclusions are contrary to all other surveys on readability of texts.]\"<ref>{{cite book |title= About Face: Reviving the Rules of Typography|last= Jury|first= David|year= 2004|publisher= Rotovision SA|location= Switzerland|isbn= 2-88046-798-5 |page=52}} The bracketed words in the text are Jury's. For the rest of the quoted passage, Jury appears to have drawn on a report by Alison Shaw, ''Print for Partial Sight: A Research Report'', Library Association, 1969, that he identifies on pages 51 and 247. In Jury's endnote on page 247, he points to \"research done before, and at approximately the same time as, this 1969 report: G.W. Ovink, ''Legibility, Atmosphere-value, and Forms of Printing Types'', Leiden, 1938. Donald Paterson, Miles A. Tinker, ''How to Make Type Readable'', Harper & Brothers, 1949. Sir Cyril Birt, ''A Psychological Study of Typography'', Cambridge University Press, 1959. Miles A. Tinker, ''Legibility of Print'', Iowa State University Press, 1965. Miles A. Tinker, ''Bases for effective reading'', University of Minnesota Press, 1965. Herbert Spencer, ''The Visible Word'', Lund Humphries, 1968. The ATypI Legibility Research Committee initial report (no named author), ''Journal of Typographic Research'', 1968.\"</ref>\n\nA widespread observation is that increased sentence spacing creates \"rivers\"<ref>[[#Dow95|Dowding 1995]]. p. 29; [[#Fel03|Felici 2003]]. p. 80; [[#Fog08|Fogarty 2008]]. p. 85; [[#Sch97|Schriver 1997]]. 270; [[#Smi09|Smith 2009]]; [[#Squ06|Squire 2006]]. p. 65.</ref> or \"holes\"<ref>[[#Gar06|Garner 2006]]. p. 83; [[#Wil07|John Wiley & Sons 2007]]. p. 153; [[#Jur09|Jury 2009]]. p. 58; [[#Jur04|Jury 2004]]. p. 92; [[#Rol93|Rollo 1993]]. p. 4; [[#Wil03|Williams 2003]]. p. 13.</ref> within text, making it visually unattractive, distracting, and difficult to locate the end of sentences.<ref>[[#Cra06|Craig and Scala 2006]]. p. 64; The Design and Publishing Center, cited in [[#Rho99|Rhodes 1999]]; Garzia, R.P, and R. London. ''Vision and Reading''. (1995). Mosby Publishing, St Louis. Cited in [[#Sca02|Scales 2002]]. p. 4. Other studies show that \"irregular and uneven spacing\" disrupts the text and may slow the reader; [[#Wil07|John Wiley & Sons Australia 2007]]. p. 270. The context of the \"irregular and uneven spacing\" is concerning justified text.</ref> Comprehensive works on typography describe the negative effect on readability caused by inconsistent spacing,<ref name=\"twofer\">[[#Dow95|Dowding 1995]]. p. 5; [[#Jur04|Jury 2004]]. p. 92.</ref> which is supported in a 1981 study which found that \"comprehension was significantly less accurate with the river condition.\"<ref>[[#Cam81|Campbell, Marchetti, and Mewhort 1981]]. cited in [[#Sch97|Schriver 1997]]. p. 270.</ref> Another 1981 study on [[Cathode Ray Tube]] (CRT) displays concluded that \"more densely packed text is read more efficiently \u2026 than is more loosely packed text.\"<ref>[[#Kol81|Kolers, Duchinsky, and Ferguson 1981]].</ref> This statement is supported in other works as well.<ref name=\"twofer\"/>\nCanadian typographer Geoffrey Dowding suggests possible explanations of this phenomenon: \n<blockquote>A carefully composed text page appears as an orderly series of strips of black separated by horizontal channels of white space. Conversely, in a slovenly setting the tendency is for the page to appear as a grey and muddled pattern of isolated spats, this effect being caused by the over-widely separated words. The normal, easy, left-to-right movement of the eye is slowed down simply because of this separation; further, the short letters and serifs are unable to discharge an important function \u2013 that of keeping the eye on \"the line\". The eye also tends to be confused by a feeling of ''vertical'' emphasis, that is, an up & down movement, induced by the relative isolation of the words & consequent insistence of the ascending and descending letters. This movement is further emphasized by those \"rivers\" of white which are the inseparable & ugly accompaniment of all carelessly set text matter.<ref>[[#Dow95|Dowding 1995]]. pp. 5\u20136, 29.</ref></blockquote>\nSome studies suggest that readability can be improved by breaking sentences into separate units of thought\u2014or varying the internal spacing of sentences. Mid-20th century research on this topic resulted in inconclusive findings.<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]; [[#Nor|North and Jenkins 1951]]. p. 68., cited in [[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. p. 125.</ref> A 1980 study split sentences into 1\u20135 word phrases with additional spacing between segments. The study concluded that there was no significant difference in efficacy, but that a wider study was needed.<ref>[[#Har|Hartley 1980]]. pp. 62, 64\u201365, 70, 74\u201375. The sentences averaged 25.4 words each. Hartley does not identify which font type and sentence spacing method was used in his study. The author notes other studies, three of which found a positive correlation between segmenting parts of sentences and reading efficacy, three that noted no significance, and one that indicated a negative effect. The additional studies noted were: \"Coleman and Kim, 1961; Epstein, 1967; and Murray, 1976 (with positive results); those of Nahinsky, 1956; Hartley and Burnhill, 1971; and Burnhill et al., 1975 (with non-significant results); and that of Klare et al., 1957 (a negative result)\" (64).</ref> Numerous other similar studies in 1951\u20131991 resulted in disparate and inconclusive findings.<ref>[[#Bev91|Bever 1991]]. pp. 78\u201380, 83\u201387. The text materials used in the research inserted various characters, such as [[pound sign]]s in the spaces between phrases, visually interrupting the \"river\" effect. This study also analyzed various spacing techniques. It did not vary spacing between sentences or identify font type used, and concluded that \"isolating major phrases within extra spaces facilitates reading.\" The article lists similar studies. The research in 14 studies in 1951\u20131986 correlated with the findings in the article, and six studies in 1957\u20131984 were inconclusive.</ref> \nFinally, although various studies have been conducted on the readability of proportional vs. monospaced fonts, the studies typically did not decrease sentence spacing when using proportional fonts, or did not specify whether sentence spacing was changed.<ref>[[#Pay67|Payne 1967]]. pp. 125\u2013136; [[#Bla93|Black and Watts 1993]].</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[History of sentence spacing]]\n*[[Sentence spacing in language and style guides]]\n*[[Sentence spacing in digital media]]\n*[[Space (punctuation)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite journal |last1= Black|first1= Allison|last2= Watts|first2= Darren|year= 1993|title= Proofreading Monospaced and Proportionally-spaced Typefaces|journal= Visible Language|publisher= Visible Language|volume= 27|issue= 3|pages= 364\u2013377|ref=Bla93}}\n* {{cite journal |doi= 10.1080/00140138108924885 |last1= Campbell|first1= A.J.|last2= Marchetti|first2= F.M.|last3= Mewhort|first3= D.J.K.|year= 1981|title= Reading Speed and Text Production: A Note on Right-Justification Techniques|journal= Ergonomics|publisher= Taylor & Francis|volume= 24|issue= 8|pages= 633\u2013640|ref=Cam81}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Clinton|first1= Gregory|last2= Branch|first2=Robert Maribe|last3= Holschuh|first3= D.|last4= Shewanown|first4= S.|year= 2003|title= Online Reading Performance Time as a Function of Text Layout: Roundtable Paper Presented at the 2003 AECT Leadership & Technology International Convention, Anaheim, Ca|ref= Cli03}}\n* {{cite book |title= Designing With Type: The Essential Guide to Typography|edition= 5th|last1= Craig|first1= James|last2= Scala|first2= Irene Korol|year= 2006|publisher= Watson-Guptill|location= New York|isbn= 0-8230-1413-4 |ref=Cra06}}\n* {{cite book |title= Finer Points in the Spacing & Arrangement of Type|edition= Revised|last= Dowding|first= Geoffrey|year= 1995|publisher= Hartley & Marks Publishers|location= Vancouver, BC|isbn= 0-88179-119-9 |ref=Dow95}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Complete Manual of Typography|last1= Felici|first1= James|year= 2003|publisher= Peachpit Press|location= Berkeley, CA|isbn= 0-321-12730-7 |ref= Fel03}}\n* {{cite book|title= Grammar Girl's Quick and Dirty Tips for Better Writing|last= Fogarty|first= Mignon|year= 2008|publisher= Holt Paperbacks|location= New York|isbn= 978-0-8050-8831-1|ref= Fog08|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/grammargirlsquic0000foga}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Redbook: A Manual on Legal Style|edition= 2nd|last= Garner|first= Bryan A.|author2= Jeff Newman, Tiger Jackson|year= 2006|publisher= Thompson West|isbn= 978-0-314-16891-7|ref= Gar06|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/redbook_gar_2006_00_9936}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Haber|first1= Ralph Norman|last2= Haber|first2= Lyn R.|year= 1981|title= Visual Components of the Reading Process|journal= Visible Language|publisher= Visible Language|volume= 15|issue= 2|pages= 147\u2013182|ref=Hab81}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Hartley|first1= James|year= 1980|title= Spatial Cues in Text|journal= Visible Language|publisher= Visible Language|volume= 14|issue= 1|pages= 62\u201379|ref=Har80}}\n* {{cite book |title= About Face: Reviving the Rules of Typography|last= Jury|first= David|year= 2004|publisher= Rotovision SA|location= Switzerland|isbn= 2-88046-798-5 |ref=Jur04}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.rotovision.com/images/2880468221.pdf|title=What is Typography?|author=Jury, David|year=2009|work=|publisher=Rotovision|accessdate=31 March 2010|pages=28\u201387|ref=Jur09}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Kolers|first1= Paul A. |last2= Duchinsky|first2= Robert|last3= Ferguson|first3= Dennis C.|year= 1981|title= Eye Movement Measurement of Readability of CRT Displays|journal= Human Factors|publisher= The Human Factors Society|volume= 23|issue= 5|pages= 517\u2013527|ref=Kol81 |pmid= 7319497 |doi=10.1177/001872088102300502}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://www.aect.org/events/review/PropResults.asp?submit=View+Full+Proposal.&propid=148|title= The Effects of Computer-based Text Spacing on Reading Comprehension and Reading Rate|author= Leonard, Kristi|date= 10 October 2009|publisher= AECT|accessdate= 1 February 2010|ref= Leo09|display-authors= etal|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717185321/http://www.aect.org/events/review/PropResults.asp?submit=View+Full+Proposal.&propid=148|archivedate= 17 July 2011}}\n* Loh, Christian Sebastian, Robert Maribe Branch, Saun Shewanown, and Radwan Ali. {{cite book|author=Loh, Christian Sebastian, Robert Maribe Branch, Saun Shewanown, and Radwan Ali|title=IVLA Book of Selected Readings: Selected Readings of the IVLA Annual Conference|year=2002|publisher=IVLA|chapter=The Effect of Text Spacing After the Period on Time for On-Screen Reading Tasks|ref=Loh02}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Ni|first1= Xiaopeng|last2= Branch|first2=Robert Maribe|last3= Chen|first3= Kuan-Chung|last4= Clinton|first4= Gregory|editor1-first= Phillip J|editor1-last= Sleeman|year= 2009|title= The Effects of Text Spacing on Screen Reading Time and Comprehension|journal= International Journal of Instructional Media.|volume= 36|issue= 4|ref= Bra09}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= North|first1= A. J.|last2= Jenkins|first2= L. B.|year= 1951|title= Reading Speed and Comprehension as a Function of Typography|journal= Journal of Applied Psychology|volume= 35|ref=Nor51|pmid=14861125|doi=10.1037/h0063094|issue=4|pages=225\u20138}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Payne|first1= Donald R.|year= 1967|title= Readability of Typewritten Material; Proportional Versus Standard Spacing|journal= The Journal of Typographic Research|volume= 1|issue= 2|pages= 125\u2013136|ref=Pay67}}\n* {{cite web| url= http://www.webword.com/reports/period.html| title= One Versus Two Spaces After a Period| author= Rhodes, John S.| date= 13 April 1999| work= Webword.com| accessdate= 21 March 2010| ref= Rho99| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100309110323/http://webword.com/reports/period.html| archivedate= 9 March 2010}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.icee.usm.edu/icee/conferences/Conference%20Files/ASEE2002/P2002060INSTRSCA.PDF|title=Improving Instructional Materials by Improving Document Formatting |author=Scales, Alice Y.|year= 2002|work=ASEE Southeast Section Conference|accessdate= 10 February 2010|ref=Sca02}}\n* {{cite book |title= Dynamics in Document Design|last= Schriver|first= Karen A.|year= 1997|publisher= John Wiley & Sons|location= New York, Chichester, Brisbane, Toronto, Singapore, Weinheim|isbn= 0-471-30636-3 |ref= Sch97}}\n* {{cite book |title= Getting it Right with Type|last1= Squire|first1= Victoria|last2= Willberg|first2= Hans Peter|last3= Forsmann|first3= Friedrich|year= 2006|publisher= Laurence King Publishing|location= London|isbn= 978-1-85669-474-2 |ref=Squ06}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.executive-resumes.com/2009/07/dont-date-yourself-by-using-two-spaces.html|title=Don't Date Yourself by Using Two Spaces after a Period in Your Resume!|author=Smith, Laurie|date=8 July 2009|work=Executive Resumes and Career Transition Strategies: Reflections of an Executive Resume Writer|publisher=Creative Keystrokes\u2122 Executive Resume Service|accessdate=30 March 2010|ref=Smi09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710211507/http://www.executive-resumes.com/2009/07/dont-date-yourself-by-using-two-spaces.html|archivedate=10 July 2011}}\n* {{cite book |title= Legibility of Print|last=Tinker|first=Miles A.|year= 1963|publisher= Iowa State University Press|location= Iowa|isbn= 0-8138-2450-8|ref=Tin63}}\n* {{cite book|title= Type and Layout: How Typography and Design Can Get your Message Across \u2013 Or Get in the Way|last= Wheildon|first= Colin|year= 1995|publisher= Strathmoor Press|location= Berkeley|isbn= 0-9624891-5-8|ref= Whe95|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/typelayouthowtyp0000whei}}\n* {{cite book |title= Style Manual: For Authors, Editors and Printers|edition= 6th|last= Wiley, John, & Sons Australia|year= 2007|publisher= John Wiley & Sons Australia|isbn= 978-0-7016-3648-7|ref=Wil07}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Mac is Not a Typewriter: A Style Manual for Creating Professional-level Type on Your Macintosh|edition= 2nd|last1= Williams|first1= Robin|year= 2003|publisher= Peachpit Press|location= Berkeley, CA|isbn= 0-201-78263-4 |ref= Wil03}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Typography]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sentence spacing studies''' analyse the effects of [[sentence spacing]] techniques on the [[readability]] of text. The only direct [[Observational study|scientific studies]] have been conducted by researchers from the [[University of Georgia]], for on-screen text. There are currently no direct sentence spacing studies for printed text.\n\nThe direct studies, started in 2002, analysed single, double, and triple sentence spacing to determine what was most readable on screen. The researchers concluded that their tests did not show a statistically significant difference between the various techniques, but that further testing was needed.\n\n==Effects on readability and legibility==\nClaims abound regarding the [[Typography#Readability and legibility|legibility]] and [[readability]] of the single and double sentence-spacing methods\u2014by proponents on both sides. However, typographic opinions are typically anecdotal with no basis in evidence.<ref>[[#Whe95|Wheildon 1995]]. p. 13.</ref> According to [[Miles Tinker]], \"Opinions are not always safe guides to legibility of print,\"<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. p. 50.</ref> and when direct studies are conducted, anecdotal opinions\u2014even those of experts\u2014can turn out to be false.<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. pp. 88, 108, 127, 128, 153; [[#Whe95|Wheildon 1995]]. pp. 8, 35.</ref> For example, text that seems readable at first glance may be shown to impair reading effectiveness when subjected to [[Scientific method|scientific study]].<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. pp. 50, 108, 128. A useful example is the Helvetica font, an ubiquitous font that is considered extremely legible (visually pleasing in the construction and viewing of its characters), but has been found to impair reading effectiveness (readability). See [[#Squ06|Squire 2006]]. p. 36.</ref>\n\n=== Direct studies ===\nDirect studies include those by Loh, Branch, Shewanown, & Ali (2002), Clinton, Branch, Holschuh, & Shewanown (2003) and Ni, Branch & Chen (2004) with results favouring neither single, double, nor triple spacing.<ref>[[#Leo03|Leonard et al. 2003]].</ref> The 2002 study indicated that \"the 'double space group' consistently took longer time to finish than the 'single space' group\", but the authors concluded that \"there was not enough evidence to suggest that a significant difference exists\".<ref>[[#Loh02|Loh et al., 2002]]. p. 4. This study used \"on-screen\" text in its analysis.</ref> The 2003 study analysed on-screen single, double, and triple spacing. Again, the authors stated that there was insufficient evidence to draw a conclusion.<ref>[[#Cli03|Clinton 2003.]] The study did not find \"statistically significant differences, between reading time of single and double spaces passages\".</ref> A similar study was conducted in 2009 using identical spacing variables. The authors concluded that the \"results provided insufficient evidence that time and comprehension differ significantly among different conditions of spacing between sentences\".<ref>[[#Bra09|Ni et al. 2009]]. pp. 383, 387, 390. This study \"explored the effects of spacing after the period on on-screen reading tasks through two dependent variables, reading time and reading comprehension\".</ref>\n\n===Related studies===\nThere are other studies that could be relevant to sentence spacing,<ref>[[#Rho99|Rhodes 1999]].</ref> such as the familiarity of typographic conventions on readability. Some studies indicate that \"tradition\" can increase the readability of text,<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. p. 124.</ref> and that reading is disrupted when conventional printing arrangements are disrupted or violated.<ref>[[#Hab81|Haber and Haber 1981]]. pp. 147\u2013148, 152.</ref> The standard for the Web and published books, magazines, and newspapers is single sentence spacing.<ref>[[#Wil03|Williams 2003]]. p. 13.</ref>\n[[Image:The river effect in justified text.jpg|250px|thumb|An example of the \"river\" effect in justified text]]\n\n[[David Jury]]'s book, ''What is Typography?'' notes the following: \"Changes in spacing either between letters and words, or between the words only&nbsp;... do not appear to affect legibility. [These rather extraordinary conclusions are contrary to all other surveys on readability of texts.]\"<ref>{{cite book |title= About Face: Reviving the Rules of Typography|last= Jury|first= David|year= 2004|publisher= Rotovision SA|location= Switzerland|isbn= 2-88046-798-5 |page=52}} The bracketed words in the text are Jury's. For the rest of the quoted passage, Jury appears to have drawn on a report by Alison Shaw, ''Print for Partial Sight: A Research Report'', Library Association, 1969, that he identifies on pages 51 and 247. In Jury's endnote on page 247, he points to \"research done before, and at approximately the same time as, this 1969 report: G.W. Ovink, ''Legibility, Atmosphere-value, and Forms of Printing Types'', Leiden, 1938. Donald Paterson, Miles A. Tinker, ''How to Make Type Readable'', Harper & Brothers, 1949. Sir Cyril Birt, ''A Psychological Study of Typography'', Cambridge University Press, 1959. Miles A. Tinker, ''Legibility of Print'', Iowa State University Press, 1965. Miles A. Tinker, ''Bases for effective reading'', University of Minnesota Press, 1965. Herbert Spencer, ''The Visible Word'', Lund Humphries, 1968. The ATypl Legibility Research Committee initial report (no named author), ''Journal of Typographic Research'', 1968.\"</ref>\n\nA widespread observation is that increased sentence spacing creates \"rivers\"<ref>[[#Dow95|Dowding 1995]]. p. 29; [[#Fel03|Felici 2003]]. p. 80; [[#Fog08|Fogarty 2008]]. p. 85; [[#Sch97|Schriver 1997]]. 270; [[#Smi09|Smith 2009]]; [[#Squ06|Squire 2006]]. p. 65.</ref> or \"holes\"<ref>[[#Gar06|Garner 2006]]. p. 83; [[#Wil07|John Wiley & Sons 2007]]. p. 153; [[#Jur09|Jury 2009]]. p. 58; [[#Jur04|Jury 2004]]. p. 92; [[#Rol93|Rollo 1993]]. p. 4; [[#Wil03|Williams 2003]]. p. 13.</ref> within text, making it visually unattractive, distracting, and difficult to locate the end of sentences.<ref>[[#Cra06|Craig and Scala 2006]]. p. 64; The Design and Publishing Center, cited in [[#Rho99|Rhodes 1999]]; Garzia, R.P, and R. London. ''Vision and Reading''. (1995). Mosby Publishing, St Louis. Cited in [[#Sca02|Scales 2002]]. p. 4. Other studies show that \"irregular and uneven spacing\" disrupts the text and may slow the reader; [[#Wil07|John Wiley & Sons Australia 2007]]. p. 270. The context of the \"irregular and uneven spacing\" is concerning justified text.</ref> Comprehensive works on typography describe the negative effect on readability caused by inconsistent spacing,<ref name=\"twofer\">[[#Dow95|Dowding 1995]]. p. 5; [[#Jur04|Jury 2004]]. p. 92.</ref> which is supported in a 1981 study which found that \"comprehension was significantly less accurate with the river condition.\"<ref>[[#Cam81|Campbell, Marchetti, and Mewhort 1981]]. cited in [[#Sch97|Schriver 1997]]. p. 270.</ref> Another 1981 study on [[Cathode Ray Tube]] (CRT) displays concluded that \"more densely packed text is read more efficiently \u2026 than is more loosely packed text.\"<ref>[[#Kol81|Kolers, Duchinsky, and Ferguson 1981]].</ref> This statement is supported in other works as well.<ref name=\"twofer\"/>\nCanadian typographer Geoffrey Dowding suggests possible explanations of this phenomenon: \n<blockquote>A carefully composed text page appears as an orderly series of strips of black separated by horizontal channels of white space. Conversely, in a slovenly setting the tendency is for the page to appear as a grey and muddled pattern of isolated spats, this effect being caused by the over-widely separated words. The normal, easy, left-to-right movement of the eye is slowed down simply because of this separation; further, the short letters and serifs are unable to discharge an important function \u2013 that of keeping the eye on \"the line\". The eye also tends to be confused by a feeling of ''vertical'' emphasis, that is, an up & down movement, induced by the relative isolation of the words & consequent insistence of the ascending and descending letters. This movement is further emphasized by those \"rivers\" of white which are the inseparable & ugly accompaniment of all carelessly set text matter.<ref>[[#Dow95|Dowding 1995]]. pp. 5\u20136, 29.</ref></blockquote>\nSome studies suggest that readability can be improved by breaking sentences into separate units of thought\u2014or varying the internal spacing of sentences. Mid-20th century research on this topic resulted in inconclusive findings.<ref>[[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]; [[#Nor|North and Jenkins 1951]]. p. 68., cited in [[#Tin63|Tinker 1963]]. p. 125.</ref> A 1980 study split sentences into 1\u20135 word phrases with additional spacing between segments. The study concluded that there was no significant difference in efficacy, but that a wider study was needed.<ref>[[#Har|Hartley 1980]]. pp. 62, 64\u201365, 70, 74\u201375. The sentences averaged 25.4 words each. Hartley does not identify which font type and sentence spacing method was used in his study. The author notes other studies, three of which found a positive correlation between segmenting parts of sentences and reading efficacy, three that noted no significance, and one that indicated a negative effect. The additional studies noted were: \"Coleman and Kim, 1961; Epstein, 1967; and Murray, 1976 (with positive results); those of Nahinsky, 1956; Hartley and Burnhill, 1971; and Burnhill et al., 1975 (with non-significant results); and that of Klare et al., 1957 (a negative result)\" (64).</ref> Numerous other similar studies in 1951\u20131991 resulted in disparate and inconclusive findings.<ref>[[#Bev91|Bever 1991]]. pp. 78\u201380, 83\u201387. The text materials used in the research inserted various characters, such as [[pound sign]]s in the spaces between phrases, visually interrupting the \"river\" effect. This study also analyzed various spacing techniques. It did not vary spacing between sentences or identify font type used, and concluded that \"isolating major phrases within extra spaces facilitates reading.\" The article lists similar studies. The research in 14 studies in 1951\u20131986 correlated with the findings in the article, and six studies in 1957\u20131984 were inconclusive.</ref> \nFinally, although various studies have been conducted on the readability of proportional vs. monospaced fonts, the studies typically did not decrease sentence spacing when using proportional fonts, or did not specify whether sentence spacing was changed.<ref>[[#Pay67|Payne 1967]]. pp. 125\u2013136; [[#Bla93|Black and Watts 1993]].</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[History of sentence spacing]]\n*[[Sentence spacing in language and style guides]]\n*[[Sentence spacing in digital media]]\n*[[Space (punctuation)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite journal |last1= Black|first1= Allison|last2= Watts|first2= Darren|year= 1993|title= Proofreading Monospaced and Proportionally-spaced Typefaces|journal= Visible Language|publisher= Visible Language|volume= 27|issue= 3|pages= 364\u2013377|ref=Bla93}}\n* {{cite journal |doi= 10.1080/00140138108924885 |last1= Campbell|first1= A.J.|last2= Marchetti|first2= F.M.|last3= Mewhort|first3= D.J.K.|year= 1981|title= Reading Speed and Text Production: A Note on Right-Justification Techniques|journal= Ergonomics|publisher= Taylor & Francis|volume= 24|issue= 8|pages= 633\u2013640|ref=Cam81}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Clinton|first1= Gregory|last2= Branch|first2=Robert Maribe|last3= Holschuh|first3= D.|last4= Shewanown|first4= S.|year= 2003|title= Online Reading Performance Time as a Function of Text Layout: Roundtable Paper Presented at the 2003 AECT Leadership & Technology International Convention, Anaheim, Ca|ref= Cli03}}\n* {{cite book |title= Designing With Type: The Essential Guide to Typography|edition= 5th|last1= Craig|first1= James|last2= Scala|first2= Irene Korol|year= 2006|publisher= Watson-Guptill|location= New York|isbn= 0-8230-1413-4 |ref=Cra06}}\n* {{cite book |title= Finer Points in the Spacing & Arrangement of Type|edition= Revised|last= Dowding|first= Geoffrey|year= 1995|publisher= Hartley & Marks Publishers|location= Vancouver, BC|isbn= 0-88179-119-9 |ref=Dow95}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Complete Manual of Typography|last1= Felici|first1= James|year= 2003|publisher= Peachpit Press|location= Berkeley, CA|isbn= 0-321-12730-7 |ref= Fel03}}\n* {{cite book|title= Grammar Girl's Quick and Dirty Tips for Better Writing|last= Fogarty|first= Mignon|year= 2008|publisher= Holt Paperbacks|location= New York|isbn= 978-0-8050-8831-1|ref= Fog08|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/grammargirlsquic0000foga}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Redbook: A Manual on Legal Style|edition= 2nd|last= Garner|first= Bryan A.|author2= Jeff Newman, Tiger Jackson|year= 2006|publisher= Thompson West|isbn= 978-0-314-16891-7|ref= Gar06|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/redbook_gar_2006_00_9936}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Haber|first1= Ralph Norman|last2= Haber|first2= Lyn R.|year= 1981|title= Visual Components of the Reading Process|journal= Visible Language|publisher= Visible Language|volume= 15|issue= 2|