agicon|USA}} [[Nicolas Platter]]\n*{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Orrett Prendergast]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tom Presthus]] *\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[James Prosser (soccer)|James Prosser]]\n\n==R==\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[C. W. Raines]]\n*{{flagicon|ETH}} [[Tenkir Reta]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Evan Richardson]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Roberts (soccer)|Brian Roberts]]\n*{{flagicon|RSA}} [[Neill Roberts]]\n\n==S==\n*{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Ricardo S\u00e1nchez (footballer)|Ricardo S\u00e1nchez]]\n*{{flagicon|HAI}} [[Leonel Saint-Preux]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Sanneh]]\n*{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Mike Saunders (soccer)|Mike Saunders]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Schmidt]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Schneider (soccer)|Paul Schneider]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Mark Schulte]]\n*{{flagicon|Liberia}} [[Dionysius Sebwe]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Shak]]\n*{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Garfield Shaw]]\n*{{flagicon|ETH}} [[Lencho Skibba]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Derek Smith (soccer)|Derek Smith]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Darren Spicer]]\n*{{flagicon|ROM}} [[Constantin St\u0103nici]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[John Swallen]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Bradley Swenby]]\n\n*{{flagicon|ERI}}Petros Tensae\n*{{flagicon|LBR}} [[Melvin Tarley]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kevin Taylor (soccer)|Kevin Taylor]]\n*{{flagicon|RSA}} [[Godfrey Tenoff]]\n*{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Marco Terminesi]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Johnny Torres]]\n*{{flagicon|LBR}} [[Ansu Toure]]\n\n==U==\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Sini\u0161a Ubiparipovi\u0107]]\n\n==V==\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ronald Valderrama]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Van Oekel]] \u2020\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Christopher Vorenkamp]]\n\n==W==\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Warren (goalkeeper)|Joe Warren]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marcus Watson]] \u2020\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Dale Weiler]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Greg Wheaton]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jason Willan]]\n*{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Michael Wilson (soccer)|Michael Wilson]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Nate Winkel]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Winters (soccer)|Brian Winters]]\n\n==Z==\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Morgan Zeba]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kyle Zenoni]]\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/scripts/runisa.dll?M2:gp::72011+Elements/Display+E+47116+History/+22347+13380660|title=USL-1 Team History|work=uslsoccer.com|publisher=[[United Soccer Leagues]]}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{USL-1 all-time rosters}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of soccer players by club in the United States|Minnesota Thunder]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Thunder players| ]]\n[[Category:Association football player non-biographical articles]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Andrew Barron", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All-time_Minnesota_Thunder_roster"}
{"title_page": "BCE Inc.", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = BCE Inc.\n| logo                = BCE_Inc_Logo.svg\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{tsx|BCE}}<br>{{nyse|BCE}}<br>[[S&P/TSX 60|S&P/TSX 60 component]]\n| industry            = [[Telecommunication]]s<br />[[Mass media]]\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list| Mirko Bibic (President & CEO)| Glen LeBlanc (CFO & Vice Chair, Atlantic Canada)}}\n| products            = [[Landline|Fixed line]] and <br>[[mobile phone|mobile telephony]]<br/> [[Internet]] services<br/> [[Digital television]]<br/> [[Radio broadcasting]]<br/> Print\n| revenue             = {{increase}} {{CAD|23.96 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|23.47 billion}} (FY18)\n| operating_income    = {{increase}} {{CAD|7.96 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|7.38 billion}} (FY18)\n| net_income          = {{increase}} {{CAD|3.25 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|2.97 billion}} (FY18)\n| assets              = {{ increase}} {{CAD|60.15 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|57.10 billion}} (FY18)\n| num_employees       = 52,100\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| parent              = \n| subsid              = [[Bell Canada]]<br>[[Bell Media]]<br>Bell Technical Solutions<br>[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]] (37.5%)<br>[[Bell Mobility]]<br>[[Bell Aliant]] <br> [[Virgin Mobile Canada]] <br> [[Bell Internet]] <br> [[Bell TV]] <br> [[Bell Fibe TV]] <br> [[Fibe (Bell Aliant)|Fibe]] <br> [[Bell MTS]] <br> [[Lucky Mobile]]<br>[[The Source (retailer)]]<br> [[Glentel Inc.]] (50%)<br> [[Northwestel]]\n| foundation          = 1983\n| location            = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n| former_names        = Bell Canada Enterprises Inc. (1983\u20131988)\n| homepage            = {{URL|http://www.bce.ca/|bce.ca}}\n}}\n\n'''BCE Inc.''', formerly '''Bell Canada Enterprises Inc.''', is a [[publicly traded]] telecommunications [[holding company]] for the [[Bell Canada]] corporate group and for various [[mass media]] assets under BCE's subsidiary, [[Bell Media]]. Founded through a corporate reorganization in 1983 when Bell Canada, [[Northern Telecom]], and other related companies all became subsidiaries of Bell Canada Enterprises Inc., the company is one of Canada's largest corporations. The company is headquartered at 1 Carrefour Alexander-Graham-Bell in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada.  \n\nIn addition to its two major subsidiaries, Bell Canada (including [[Bell Aliant]], [[Bell Mobility]], [[Bell TV]], [[Bell Media]], [[Bell Fibe TV]], [[Virgin Mobile Canada]], and [[Lucky Mobile]]) and Bell Media (including the [[CTV Television Network]], [[CTV 2]] system, dozens of speciality television channels including [[The Sports Network|TSN]], [[CTV News Channel (Canada)|CTV News Channel]], [[CTV Drama Channel]], [[CTV Sci-Fi Channel]], [[MuchMusic|Much]] and [[E! (Canadian TV channel)|E!]] and dozens of radio properties), BCE also owns 18% of the [[Montreal Canadiens]] [[ice hockey]] club, and (together with BCE's pension plan) a 37.5% interest in [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]] (owner of several Toronto sports franchises).<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/bell-rogers-now-official-owners-of-mlse/article4493958/{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/story/2011/12/09/sp-nhl-canadiens-bell.html|title=Bell to keep Canadiens stake|author=The Canadian Press|work=[[CBC.ca]]|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref> Several regional and local telecommunications companies (including [[Bell MTS]], [[Northwestel]], [[T\u00e9l\u00e9bec]], [[NorthernTel]], and [[Dryden Municipal Telephone Service]]) are direct subsidiaries of BCE rather than under Bell Canada.\n\nBCE Inc. is a component of the [[S&P/TSX 60]] and is listed with the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] ([[Toronto Stock Exchange|TSX]]: [https://web.tmxmoney.com/quote.php?qm_symbol=BCE BCE]) and the [[New York Stock Exchange]] ([[New York Stock Exchange|NYSE]]:[https://www.nyse.com/quote/XNYS:BCE BCE]). It was ranked as Canada's 17th largest corporation by revenue in 2014<ref>[http://www.financialpost.com/news/fp500/2014/index.html FP500: 2014]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> and as the ninth-largest by capitalization in 2015.<ref>[http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lists-and-rankings/best-stocks/investor-500-2015-canadas-biggest-15-companies-by-market-cap/ Investor 500 2015: ''Canada\u2019s Biggest 15 companies by market cap'', Canadian Business, June 16, 2015].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:BellCanada1902.png|thumb|Logo used by the Bell Telephone Company of Canada from 1902 to 1922]]\nThe Bell Telephone Company of Canada Ltd. was created by an [[act of Parliament]] on 29 April 1880. Later known as [[Bell Canada]], its charter granted it the right to construct telephone lines alongside all public rights-of-way in Canada. Under a licensing agreement with the US-based [[Bell Telephone Company|American Bell Telephone Company]], Bell also manufactured telephones and telephone equipment, an activity that would be spun off in a separate company that later became Northern Telecom and then [[Nortel Networks]].\n\nIn 1983, all of the Bell Canada group of companies (also known as the \"Bell Group\") were placed under a new holding company, Bell Canada Enterprises Inc. (BCE). This corporate reorganization resulted in Bell Canada and its subsidiaries, including Northern Telecom (later Nortel Networks) and over 80 others, becoming subsidiaries of the new holding company, BCE. Under the new parent, each company was owned directly by BCE, which had the benefit of freeing the manufacturing company, Nortel, and other holdings from the heavily regulated telephone company, Bell Canada. Under a variety of leaders, BCE has embarked on a series of [[Diversification (marketing strategy)|diversifications]], [[Consolidation (business)|consolidations]], and [[Strategic management|corporate strategies]].<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/bell-canada-enterprises-inc/ Bell Canada Enterprises, The Canadian Encyclopedia]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> In 1988, Bell Canada Enterprises was renamed BCE Inc.\n\n===Diversification and expansion===\nIn 1983, [[A. Jean de Grandpr\u00e9]], chairman of Bell Canada, was appointed as the first chairman and [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of BCE.<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/04/29/Bell-Canada-Enterprises-Inc-has-become-the-new-parent/8282420436800/ ''Bell Canada Enterprises Inc. has become the new parent...'', UPI, April 29, 1983].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  The company soon embarked on a major diversification into property development, the energy sector, financial services, and other sectors.  Within a few years, it became the first Canadian company to report CAD$1 billion in profits.\n\nWhen [[Jean Monty]] assumed the job of CEO in 1998, he pursued a convergence strategy, attempting to combine both content creation and distribution within BCE, and to take greater advantage of the emerging Internet market. BCE's acquisition in 2000 (and subsequent financing) of overseas carrier [[Teleglobe]] cost billions of dollars. BCE sold Teleglobe two years later; Jean Monty resigned and was succeeded by [[Michael Sabia]] as CEO.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Macklem\n  | first = Katherine\n  | title = Monty quits as BCE CEO\n  | publisher = Maclean's Magazine\n  | date = 2002-05-06\n  | url = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=M1SEC677092\n  | accessdate = 2007-06-29\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/2002/04/25/0425monty.html | work=Forbes | title=BCE Backs Away From The Full Monty | date=2002-04-25 | first=Mark | last=Lewis}}</ref>\n\n===Refocus on core business===\nMichael Sabia refocused BCE on its core telecommunications business, prompting BCE to buy back the 20% share in Bell Canada that it had sold in 1999 to [[Ameritech]] (which was subsequently acquired by [[SBC Corporation]]).<ref>{{cite press release\n |title=BCE to Own 100 per cent of Bell Canada \n |publisher=BCE, Inc. \n |date=2002-06-28 \n |url=http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/bce/2002/6/28/69087.html \n |accessdate=2007-06-29 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921172540/http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/bce/2002/6/28/69087.html \n |archivedate=2007-09-21 \n}}</ref> BCE also spun off operating units that it did not consider to be core to its business, including [[Emergis]] in 2004, and [[CTVglobemedia|Bell Globemedia]] and [[Telesat Canada]] in 2006.\n\nOn February 1, 2006, stating the need to remain competitive, Bell Canada announced job cuts of 3,000 to 4,000 employees by the end of 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bell-canada-cuts-471-ontario-jobs-1.589239|title=Bell Canada cuts 471 Ontario jobs {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn April 28, BCE announced that CEO Michael Sabia was taking a 455% pay increase, his salary being raised from [[Canadian dollar|C$]]1.21 million a year to $6.71 million a year.  The pay included a $1.25 million salary, a $2.2 million bonus that Sabia converted to deferred share units, a long-term incentive payout of $3 million and other compensation, the filing shows. Bell Canada also posted record revenue increases for the previous fiscal year.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nUnder pressure from [[investors]], on October 11, 2006, BCE announced it would be wound down, with its remaining assets converted to an [[income trust]] so its income could be distributed directly to [[shareholders]] through [[dividends]], avoiding [[corporate taxes]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bell-canada-to-convert-to-income-trust-1.580316|title=Bell Canada to convert to income trust {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> The new entity was planned to be named \"Bell Canada Income Fund\". As part of this restructuring, Bell Aliant offered to take Bell Nordiq private, while remaining separate from the new Bell trust.<ref>[http://www.cnw.ca/en/releases/archive/October2006/11/c6730.html BCE to be wound down, Bell Canada to convert to income trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617131549/http://www.cnw.ca/en/releases/archive/October2006/11/c6730.html |date=2008-06-17 }}, BCE press release, October 11, 2006</ref> Due to [[Income trust#Canada|announced changes in taxation law]] by the Canadian federal government, on December 12, 2006, BCE announced it would not proceed with its planned conversion to an income trust.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/bce-dies-bell-lives-as-trust/article18174524/ ''BCE dies Bell lives as trust'', The Globe and Mail, Oct. 12, 2006]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/business/story.html?id=beaeacf6-31e2-40cb-9e5c-66ab290453e2 BCE drops its income-trust plan, Montreal Gazette, December 13, 2011].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> It then started planning a restructuring that would have eliminated the BCE holding company,<ref>{{cite press release\n  | title = Bell announces 2007 business outlook&nbsp;\u2014 Improving revenue and EBITDA growth in 2007 guidance\n  | publisher = BCE, Inc.\n  | date = 2006-12-12\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2006/12/12/74065.html\n  | accessdate = 2007-01-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070127225232/http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2006/12/12/74065.html| archivedate= 27 January 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  | title = United States SEC filing, June 12, 2007, Form 6-K\n  | publisher = Securities and Exchange Commission\n  | date = 2007-06-12\n  | url = http://www.secinfo.com/d16Vm2.uv.htm\n  | accessdate = 2007-06-30\n}}</ref> but this was put on hold when the company began attracting [[takeover]] bids.\n\n===Proposed takeover===\nDue to its stagnant [[share price]], starting in April 2007, BCE was courted for acquisition by pension funds and private equity groups, including a consortium led by the [[Canada Pension Plan]] Investment Board (with [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]] as one of the participants), a consortium led by the [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]] (OTPP), and a consortium that included [[Cerberus Capital Management]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Telus's exit likely to pull down price of BCE bids \n |publisher=Reuters \n |date=2002-06-27 \n |url=http://www.globeinvestor.com/servlet/story/ROC.20070627.2007-06-27T170950Z_01_N27295009_RTRIDST_0_BUSINESS-BCE-BIDS-COL/GIStory/ \n |accessdate=2007-06-29 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927174353/http://www.globeinvestor.com/servlet/story/ROC.20070627.2007-06-27T170950Z_01_N27295009_RTRIDST_0_BUSINESS-BCE-BIDS-COL/GIStory/ \n |archivedate=2007-09-27 \n}}</ref>  On June 30, 2007, BCE accepted a bid of $42.75 per share in cash, for a total valuation of $51.7 billion, from the group led by the OTPP, and including [[Providence Equity Partners]], [[Madison Dearborn Partners]], [[Merrill Lynch]] Global Private Equity, and [[Toronto-Dominion Bank]]. The proposed deal would have been the largest acquisition in Canadian history and the largest [[leveraged buyout]] ever.<ref name=\"CanWest-BCETeachers\">{{cite web\n |title=Teachers win BCE bid \n |publisher=CanWest News service \n |date=2007-06-30 \n |url=http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=86dacb18-6f44-4c27-9c38-27e9e48f247b&k=2695 \n |accessdate=2007-06-30 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206115626/http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=86dacb18-6f44-4c27-9c38-27e9e48f247b&k=2695 \n |archivedate=2007-12-06 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-banks\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Sorkin\n  | first = Andrew Ross\n  | last2 = de la Merced\n  | first2 = Michael J.\n  | title = Banks' Terms Imperil Deal to Buy Out Bell Canada\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | date = 2008-05-19\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/19/business/worldbusiness/19deal.html\n  | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}</ref>\nThe deal was approved by BCE shareholders,<ref>{{cite news\n |title=BCE holders approve giant buyout \n |publisher=Toronto Star \n |date=2007-09-22 \n |url=https://www.thestar.com/printArticle/259285 \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071201110321/http://www.thestar.com/printArticle/259285 \n |archive-date=2007-12-01 \n |accessdate=2007-10-01 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n[[Quebec Superior Court]]<ref name=\"CBC-QSCApproval\">{{cite news\n  | author = CBC News\n  | title = Quebec court OK's BCE takeover, dismisses bondholders' complaints\n  | publisher = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n  | date = 2008-03-07\n  | url = http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2008/03/07/bce-ruling.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-06-20\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080508210334/http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2008/03/07/bce-ruling.html| archivedate= 8 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n(whose ruling was overturned by the [[Quebec Court of Appeal]],<ref name=\"NYT-QuebecCourt\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Austen\n  | first = Ian\n  | title = Bell Canada Takeover Is Blocked\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | date = 2008-05-22\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/22/business/worldbusiness/22bce.html\n  | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}</ref> but was later upheld by the [[Supreme Court of Canada]]<ref name=\"CP-SupremeApproval\">{{cite web|last=Beltrame |first=Julian |title=Supreme Court approves BCE deal |publisher=The Canadian Press |date=2008-06-20 |url=http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2008/06/20/5941106-cp.html |accessdate=2008-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20081004235833/http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2008/06/20/5941106-cp.html |archivedate=October 4, 2008 }}</ref>),\nand the CRTC, subject to certain conditions for its corporate governance structure to ensure that Bell remained under Canadian control.<ref name=\"CNW-CRTC-approval\">{{cite web\n  | title = CRTC approves BCE purchase with conditions\n  | publisher = CNW Group\n  | date = 2008-03-27\n  | url = http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/March2008/27/c7841.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-03}}</ref>\n(See ''[[BCE Inc v 1976 Debentureholders]]'' for further information).\n\nDue to the tightening of the [[credit market]] caused by the [[subprime mortgage crisis]], the investment banks financing the deal \u2013 led by [[Citigroup]], [[Deutsche Bank]] and the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] \u2013 started negotiations on May 16, 2008, to revise the terms of their loans with greater interest rates and greater restrictions to protect themselves.<ref name=\"NYT-banks\" /> On July 4, 2008, BCE announced that a final agreement had been reached on the terms of the purchase,<ref name=\"BCE-2008FinalAgreement\">{{cite press release\n  | title = BCE and Purchaser Enter Into Final Agreement Financing and Credit Agreements Signed\n  | publisher = BCE, Inc.\n  | date = 2008-07-04\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/07/04/74793.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-08-07\n}}</ref> with all financing in place, and Michael Sabia left BCE, with [[George A. Cope|George Cope]] assuming the position of CEO on July 11.<ref name=\"2008NewCEO-PR\">{{cite press release\n  | title = George Cope appointed to the boards of directors and as CEO of BCE Inc. and Bell Canada\n  | publisher = BCE\n  | date = 2008-07-11\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/07/11/74806.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-07-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080721042212/http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/07/11/74806.html| archivedate= 21 July 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2008, BCE announced that [[KPMG]] had informed BCE that it would not be able to issue a statement on the solvency of the company after its [[privatization]], one of the required conditions of the buyout. As a result, the purchase was cancelled.<ref name=\"CBC-BuyoutCancelled\">{{cite news\n  | author = CBC News\n  | title = BCE takeover deal dead as fight looms over $1.2B breakup fee\n  | publisher = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n  | date = 2008-12-11\n  | url = http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2008/12/11/bce-takeover.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-01-03 }}</ref><ref name=\"BCE-solvencyTest\">{{cite press release\n  | title = BCE statement regarding privatization transaction\n  | publisher = BCE, Inc.\n  | date = 2008-11-26\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/11/26/75050.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-12-03\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Expanding again into mass media===\nWith [[Shaw Communications]] purchasing the [[Global Television Network]], [[Vid\u00e9otron]] launching its wireless telephone network with video content as a key selling point,<ref name=\"CTV-Bell-Bet\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Marlow\n  | first = Iain\n  | title = Bell's Big Bet\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-10\n  | url=  https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bells-big-bet/article1703448/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913134643/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bells-big-bet/article1703448/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and the enormous popularity of wireless and Internet video and other media streams at the [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Vancouver Olympics]],<ref name=\"Bell-Vancouver-Olympics-multimedia\">{{Cite news\n  | last = McNish\n  | first = Jacquie\n  |author2=Paul Waldie\n  | title = Olympic moment turned Bell CEO into champion for mobile media\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-11\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/olympic-moment-turned-bell-ceo-into-champion-for-mobile-media/article1703769/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913134914/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/olympic-moment-turned-bell-ceo-into-champion-for-mobile-media/article1703769/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Bell once again sought to bring a content provider into its portfolio. In September 2010, Bell announced a deal to reacquire full control of the broadcasting properties owned by [[CTVglobemedia]] including the [[CTV Television Network]]. Bell also obtained a 15% interest in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', CTVglobemedia's other major asset, with the remaining 85% owned by the [[The Woodbridge Company|Thomson family]].<ref name=\"CTV-purchase\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Marlow\n  | first = Iain\n  | title = BCE-CTV deal remakes media landscape\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-10\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bce-ctv-deal-remakes-media-landscape/article1702385/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913122024/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bce-ctv-deal-remakes-media-landscape/article1702385/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nThrough this acquisition, Bell responded to an increasing trend away from traditional cable and satellite delivery channels and towards new [[digital distribution|distribution]] methods over the Internet and wireless networks.<ref name=\"CTV-purchase-analysis\">{{Cite news\n  | last = DeCloet\n  | first = Derek\n  | title = The new convergence: A lot like the old version but much, much cheaper\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-10\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/commentary/derek-decloet/the-new-convergence-a-lot-like-the-old-version-but-much-much-cheaper/article1702799/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913120117/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/commentary/derek-decloet/the-new-convergence-a-lot-like-the-old-version-but-much-much-cheaper/article1702799/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nThe CRTC approved the transaction in March 2011.<ref name=\"CRTC-approval\">{{cite web\n |author=Canadian Press \n |title=CRTC approves BCE's purchase of CTVglobemedia \n |publisher=CTV.ca \n |date=2011-03-07 \n |url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20110307/crtc-approves-ctvglobemedia-purchase-by-bce-110307/ \n |accessdate=2011-05-23 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629044310/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20110307/crtc-approves-ctvglobemedia-purchase-by-bce-110307/ \n |archivedate=29 June 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, BCE announced that it had entered an agreement to acquire [[Manitoba Telecom Services]] (MTS) in a transaction worth $3.9 billion. The deal has been approved by both companies' shareholders and [[boards of directors]], and is expected to close in late 2016 or early 2017 pending regulatory approval from the [[Competition Bureau]] and other agencies.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hardy|first1=Ian|title=BCE to acquire MTS for $3.9 billion, plans to divest one-third of the postpaid subscribers to Telus|url=http://mobilesyrup.com/2016/05/02/bce-to-acquire-mts-for-3-9-billion-plans-to-divest-one-third-of-the-postpaid-subscribers-to-telus/|publisher=MobileSyrup|accessdate=May 2, 2016|date=May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Major subsidiaries==\nAs of 2016, BCE Inc. has three main subsidiaries: [[Bell Canada]], [[Bell Mobility]], and [[Bell Media]], comprising over 80% of BCE's revenue.<ref name=\"BCE-AR-2015\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.bce.ca/investors/AR-2015/2015-bce-annual-report.pdf\n | title = BCE INC. 2015 ANNUAL REPORT\n | author = BCE Inc.\n | publisher = BCE Inc.\n | access-date = 2016-03-21\n }}</ref> [[Bell Aliant]] was a subsidiary company formed in 1999 from the merger of the four BCE-controlled telephone companies serving Canada's [[Atlantic Canada|Atlantic provinces]]. In 2016, the operations of Bell Aliant were consolidated into those of Bell Canada.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/eng/cht143.pdf CRTC Ownership structure 2015].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Bell Canada===\n{{main|Bell Canada}}\n[[File:Campus Bell in Montreal 1.jpg|thumb|[[Bell Canada]] headquarters in [[Montreal]]. The [[telecommunication]]s company is a subsidiary of BCE Inc.]]\nBell Canada formed the primary historic core of the company in central, Atlantic, and northern Canada. \n* Bell Aliant\n* Distribution (Ontario, Quebec, Atlantic) \u2013 Bell Canada, Cablevision du Nord de Quebec Inc. \n* Bell MTS\n* Bell TV \u2013 Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership\n\n===Bell Media===\n{{main|Bell Media}}\n[[File:299queenstreetwesttoronto.JPG|thumb|[[Bell Media]] headquarters at [[299 Queen Street West]] in Toronto. The company is BCE's [[mass media]] subsidiary.]]\n[[Bell Media]] is the BCE broadcast and media subsidiary. In 2000, BCE bought the [[CTV Television Network]] for $2.3 billion. The company combined CTV with its holdings in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' newspaper to form Bell Globemedia, with BCE owning 70% and [[Thomson Corporation|Thomson Newspapers]] and Woodbridge Co. Ltd. the remainder.  In 2005, BCE sold its controlling interest in Bell Globemedia for $183 million to Woodbridge, [[Torstar]], and the [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]], with BCE retaining a 20% stake.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bce-to-buy-ctv-for-1-3b-1.888285 ''BCE to buy CTV for $1.3B'', CBC.ca, September 10, 2010].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=886a24ee-5c68-4d17-864b-cdef43fe3324 ''BCE sells most of CTV and the Globe'', National Post, December 3, 2011].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> The company was subsequently renamed CTVglobemedia. In 2007, it acquired most assets of [[CHUM Limited]]. In 2010 BCE bought out the other owners, acquiring CTV's specialty television, digital media, conventional TV and radio broadcasting platforms.<ref>[http://www.ctvnews.ca/bell-canada-parent-bce-buys-ctv-inc-for-1-3b-1.551533 ''Bell Canada parent BCE buys CTV Inc. for $1.3B'', CTV.ca, September 10, 2010].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  In August 2015, BCE sold its remaining 15% stake in the Globe and Mail to Woodbridge.<ref>[http://ca.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idCAKCN0QJ2AJ20150814 Thomson family's Woodbridge buys full control of Globe and Mail, Reuters Canada, August 14, 2015].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  Bell Media's subsidiaries:\n{{col div}}\n* Bell Media TV\n* Bell Media TV \u2013 Sports Specialty Services\n* Bell Media TV \u2013 Specialty Services (other than Sports)\n* Bell Media Radio\n* Bell Media Astral \u2013 Radio, TV, & Specialty Services\n{{col div end}}\n==Other holdings==\nBelow is partial list of the holdings of the BCE conglomerate.\n\n===Montreal Canadiens===\nIn 2009, BCE partnered with the Molson family in acquiring the [[Montreal Canadiens]] Hockey Club and the [[Bell Centre]].  The $575 million purchase was termed \"the richest deal in NHL history\"; BCE's share was reported to be $40 million.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/1220/nhl-valuations-10-geoff-molson-montreal-canadiens-thin-ice.html ''Oh Canadiens: Inside The Richest Deal In NHL History'', Forbes Magazine, 12/02/2010].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment===\nIn 2011, together with [[Rogers Communications]] and Kilmer Sports (holding company of [[Larry Tanenbaum]]), BCE acquired [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]], owner of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] professional hockey team.  BCE's interest is held in partnership with Rogers Communications through the holding company 8047286 Canada Inc., 50% owned by Rogers and 50% by BCE holding company 7680147 Canada Inc., which is in turn 74.67% owned by BCE and 25.33% by BCE Master Trust Fund (investment fund of Bell's pension plan).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/892971/bell-acquires-ownership-position-in-maple-leaf-sports-and-entertainment-mlse|title=Bell acquires ownership position in Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment \u2013 MLSE|author=BCE Inc.|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKilmer Sports and BCE also co-own the [[Toronto Argonauts]], a team the companies purchased in 2015; BCE and Kilmer each own 50% of the team.<ref name=bellannualreport>{{cite web|url=http://www.bce.ca/investors/AR-2015/2015-bce-annual-report.pdf|title=Leading the way in communications|year=2016|accessdate=2016-03-30|publisher=BCE Inc.}}</ref>\n\n==Past holdings==\n===BCE Development===\nBCE Development was founded as '''Daon Development''' by Vancouver-based developer [[Jack Poole]] in 1964. In the mid-1970s, Daon became known for expanding aggressively in the United States. The company first entered the American market in 1976 and nearly quadrupled its total assets to $1.67 billion in four years.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1985-02-03/realestate/re-13512_1_bell-canada ''Bell Canada to Acquire Daon Development Co. : Seeks Controlling Interest in Firm Whose Lightning Rise Ended With the Recession'', LA Times, February 3, 1985].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  It borrowed heavily to finance deals for premium office space and condominium conversions.  By 1981, the company had assets worth more than $2 billion. When interest rates soared, however, Daon was caught overextended, could not meet its debt payments, and was forced into a major restructuring with its bankers. In 1985, BCE acquired 68% of Daon from its creditors and changed its name to BCE Development Corporation in February 1986. In March 1986, it agreed to acquire US$1 billion of commercial real estate from the American subsidiary of the Oxford Development Group Ltd., more than doubling BCED's portfolio. BCE stated its goal was to convert from a land developer to a developer of prime commercial properties.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/14/business/business-people-chairman-rebuilding-former-daon-corp.html ''Chairman rebuilding former Daon Corp.'', NY Times, March 14, 1986].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\nIn July 1990, BCE Inc. sold 50% ownership in BCE Development to Carena Developments  Ltd. (controlled by the [[Edper Investments|Toronto branch of the Bronfman family]]).  BCED was renamed Brookfield Development Inc. (now [[Brookfield Asset Management]]) followed in 1994 by the remaining 50%.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-07-03/business/9002230660_1_firm-canadian-changed ''BCE Development Changes Its Name'', Chicago Tribune, July 3, 1990].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2690500032.html Brookfield Properties Corporation, Encyclopedia.com].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://brookfieldofficeproperties.com/_Global/25/img/content/Files/Timeline/Brookfield%20Office%20Properties%20History%20revised%201.11.pdf Brookfield Office Properties history].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Montreal Trust===\nIn March 1989, BCE bought a 64% stake in [[Montreal Trust]] from [[Power Financial]] for $547-million.  The diversification was considered a \"natural evolution\" due to BCE's long-standing interest in financial services, its familiarity in selling services to the public, and its in-house money management operations.  In 1993, BCE sold Montreal Trust to [[Scotiabank]] for about $290-million, taking a substantial loss.<ref>[http://business.financialpost.com/news/fp-street/rogers-bank-plans-lessons-from-bce ''Rogers bank plans: Lessons from BCE'', Financial Post, September 7, 2011].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Nortel Networks===\n[[File:BellPayPhone3.jpg|thumb|upright|A Bell [[Nortel payphones#Millennium|Nortel Millennium]] payphone, introduced in the 1990s. Nortel was a BCE subsidiary from 1983 to 2000.]] \nWhen BCE was created in 1983, [[Northern Telecom]] was transferred from a subsidiary of CRTC-regulated Bell Canada to a non-regulated subsidiary of BCE. In 1998, with Nortel's acquisition of [[Bay Networks]], the company's name was changed to Nortel Networks. As a consequence of the stock transaction used to purchase Bay Networks, BCE's holding was diluted to a minority stake. In 2000, BCE [[spun out]] Nortel, distributing its stock in Nortel to its shareholders. Nortel's share price collapsed with the dot-com crash of 2000 and combined with a mishandling of a subsequent accounting investigation, the company never fully recovered. It was liquidated in 2009.<ref>[http://www.canadianbusiness.com/technology-news/nortel-collapse-of-a-giant/ ''Nortel \u2013 Collapse of a giant'', Canadian Business, January 14, 2009].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://business.financialpost.com/executive/leadership/lessons-from-nortel-acquisitions-spree-bad-management-calls-led-to-tech-giants-fall-study-says?__lsa=2d67-e92b Lessons from Nortel: Acquisitions spree, bad management calls led to tech giant\u2019s fall, study says, Financial Post, March 17, 2014].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Teleglobe Inc.===\nIn 1987, BCE purchased a 30% stake in Memotec Data Corporation for $196 million.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AIaZOlcgG28C&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=BCE+acquires+memotec&source=bl&ots=fy-jSQ0pBn&sig=0v3nvWA-GEBcea0yR3MfdlZ3nPk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-5qCmq63LAhVEzGMKHWHyAuYQ6AEIJDAC#v=onepage&q=BCE%20acquires%20memotec&f=false Babe, Robert E.  Telecommunications in Canada: Technology, Industry, and Government. University of Toronto Press, 1990.  Page 30.] {{ISBN|0802067387}}.  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> When Memotec purchased international telecommunications carrier Teleglobe Canada from the Canadian government in 1987, the company was renamed Teleglobe Inc. In March 2000, BCE announced the purchase of the Teleglobe shares it did not own for $9.65 billion.<ref>[http://www.itworldcanada.com/article/bce-goes-international-with-teleglobe/33884 ''BCE goes International with Teleglobe'', IT Canada, March 9, 2000].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> In April 2002, BCE announced it was cutting off long-term funding of Teleglobe, would give up on the company, and take a charge of up to $8.5 billion.<ref>[http://www.lightreading.com/bce-sells-last-of-teleglobe/d/d-id/587290 ''BCE sells last of Teleglobe'', Light Reading, 1/2/2003].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> In 2005, Teleglobe was sold to the [[Tata Group]] and is now known as [[VSNL International Canada]]. In September 2002, it sold its voice and data business for $197 million.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/teleglobe-sells-voice-and-data-business-1.335698 Teleglobe sells voice and data business, CBC, September 19, 2002].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Telesat Canada===\nIn 1970, Bell Canada acquired a minority interest in satellite telecommunications carrier [[Telesat Canada]]. In 1998, BCE raised its stake to 100% at a cost of $158 million for the 42% of shares it did not already own.<ref>[http://www.joc.com/maritime-news/canadas-bce-sell-stake-british-firm_19980513.html ''Canada's BCE sells stake in British Firm'',  Journal of Commerce, May 13, 1998].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  In December 2006, BCE announced the sale of Telesat to [[Loral Space & Communications]] and the [[Public Sector Pension Investment Board]] for CAD$3.28 billion.\n\n===TransCanada Pipelines===\nIn 1983, BCE acquired a controlling 42% stake in [[TransCanada PipeLines Limited]] (TCPL). In 1990, it announced its departure from the energy sector and sold its stake in TCPL for $1.1 billion.<ref>[http://www.referenceforbusiness.com/history2/87/BCE-Inc.html#ixzz42BF1AMZ0 BCE Inc. \u2013 Company Profile, Reference for Business]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n== Corporate governance ==\nBCE Inc.\u2019s ISS Governance QualityScore as of December 3, 2019 is 2.  The pillar scores are Audit: 1; Board: 3; Shareholder Rights: 3; Compensation: 3. \n\nCorporate governance scores are provided to [[Yahoo Finance]] by [[Institutional Shareholder Services]] (ISS).  Scores denote a [https://www.wisegeek.com/what-is-a-decile-rank.htm decile rank] relative to index or region. A decile score of 1 denotes the lowest governance risk, while a score of 10 denotes the highest governance risk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/BCE/profile/|title=BCE, Inc. (BCE) Company Profile & Facts - Yahoo Finance|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\n=== Board of directors ===\nAs of March 2020, the current [[board of directors]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce.ca/about-bce/leadership-team/board-members|title=Board Members {{!}} BCE Inc.|website=www.bce.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> are:  Barry K. Allen, Mirko Bibic, Sophie Brochu, Robert E. Brown, David F. Denison, Robert P. Dexter, Ian Greenberg, Katherine Lee, Monique F. Leroux, Calin Rovinescu, Karen Sheriff, Robert C. Simmonds, and Paul R. Weiss. \n\nSince inception, BCE has had ''five'' [[CEO]]s:{{col div}}\n*[[A. Jean de Grandpr\u00e9]]: 1983\u20131988\n*[[Jean Monty]]: 1988\u20132002\n*[[Michael Sabia]]: 2002\u20132008\n*[[George A. Cope]]: 2008\u20132020\n*[[Mirko Bibic]]: Current{{col div end}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|http://www.bce.ca}}\n\n{{Bell Canada Enterprises}}\n{{Bell Media}}\n{{Morningstar National Bank Qu\u00e9bec Index}}<!--cat sort position-->\n{{S&P/TSX 60}}<!--cat sort position-->\n\n[[Category:Companies acquired by Bell Canada Enterprises| 01]]\n[[Category:Bell Canada|.01]]\n[[Category:Bell System]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Holding companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Information technology companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Media companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Canada]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Corporate spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Canadian companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Holding companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:1983 establishments in Quebec]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = BCE Inc.\n| logo                = BCE_Inc_Logo.svg\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{tsx|BCE}}<br>{{nyse|BCE}}<br>[[S&P/TSX 60|S&P/TSX 60 component]]\n| industry            = [[Telecommunication]]s<br />[[Mass media]]\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list| Mirko Bibic (President & CEO)| Glen LeBlanc (CFO & Vice Chair, Atlantic Canada)}}\n| products            = [[Landline|Fixed line]] and <br>[[mobile phone|mobile telephony]]<br/> [[Internet]] services<br/> [[Digital television]]<br/> [[Radio broadcasting]]<br/> Print\n| revenue             = {{increase}} {{CAD|23.96 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|23.47 billion}} (FY18)\n| operating_income    = {{increase}} {{CAD|7.96 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|7.38 billion}} (FY18)\n| net_income          = {{increase}} {{CAD|3.25 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|2.97 billion}} (FY18)\n| assets              = {{ increase}} {{CAD|60.15 billion}} (FY19) {{CAD|57.10 billion}} (FY18)\n| num_employees       = 52,100\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| parent              = \n| subsid              = [[Bell Canada]]<br>[[Bell Media]]<br>Bell Technical Solutions<br>[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]] (37.5%)<br>[[Bell Mobility]]<br>[[Bell Aliant]] <br> [[Virgin Mobile Canada]] <br> [[Bell Internet]] <br> [[Bell TV]] <br> [[Bell Fibe TV]] <br> [[Fibe (Bell Aliant)|Fibe]] <br> [[Bell MTS]] <br> [[Lucky Mobile]]<br>[[The Source (retailer)]]<br> [[Glentel Inc.]] (50%)<br> [[Northwestel]]\n| foundation          = 1983\n| location            = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n| former_names        = Bell Canada Enterprises Inc. (1983\u20131988)\n| homepage            = {{URL|http://www.bce.ca/|bce.ca}}\n}}\n\n'''BCE Inc.''', formerly '''Bell Canada Enterprises Inc.''', is a [[publicly traded]] telecommunications [[holding company]] for the [[Bell Canada]] corporate group and for various [[mass media]] assets under BCE's subsidiary, [[Bell Media]]. Founded through a corporate reorganization in 1983 when Bell Canada, [[Northern Telecom]], and other related companies all became subsidiaries of Bell Canada Enterprises Inc., the company is one of Canada's largest corporations. The company is headquartered at 1 Carrefour Alexander-Graham-Bell in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada.  \n\nIn addition to its two major subsidiaries, Bell Canada (including [[Bell Aliant]], [[Bell Mobility]], [[Bell TV]], [[Bell Media]], [[Bell Fibe TV]], [[Virgin Mobile Canada]], and [[Lucky Mobile]]) and Bell Media (including the [[CTV Television Network]], [[CTV 2]] system, dozens of speciality television channels including [[The Sports Network|TSN]], [[CTV News Channel (Canada)|CTV News Channel]], [[CTV Drama Channel]], [[CTV Sci-Fi Channel]], [[MuchMusic|Much]] and [[E! (Canadian TV channel)|E!]] and dozens of radio properties), BCE also owns 18% of the [[Montreal Canadiens]] [[ice hockey]] club, and (together with BCE's pension plan) a 37.5% interest in [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]] (owner of several Toronto sports franchises).<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/bell-rogers-now-official-owners-of-mlse/article4493958/{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/story/2011/12/09/sp-nhl-canadiens-bell.html|title=Bell to keep Canadiens stake|author=The Canadian Press|work=[[CBC.ca]]|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref> Several regional and local telecommunications companies (including [[Bell MTS]], [[Northwestel]], [[T\u00e9l\u00e9bec]], [[NorthernTel]], and [[Dryden Municipal Telephone Service]]) are direct subsidiaries of BCE rather than under Bell Canada.\n\nBCE Inc. is a component of the [[S&P/TSX 60]] and is listed with the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] ([[Toronto Stock Exchange|TSX]]: [https://web.tmxmoney.com/quote.php?qm_symbol=BCE BCE]) and the [[New York Stock Exchange]] ([[New York Stock Exchange|NYSE]]:[https://www.nyse.com/quote/XNYS:BCE BCE]). It was ranked as Canada's 17th largest corporation by revenue in 2014<ref>[http://www.financialpost.com/news/fp500/2014/index.html FP500: 2014]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> and as the ninth-largest by capitalization in 2015.<ref>[http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lists-and-rankings/best-stocks/investor-500-2015-canadas-biggest-15-companies-by-market-cap/ Investor 500 2015: ''Canada\u2019s Biggest 15 companies by market cap'', Canadian Business, June 16, 2015].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:BellCanada1902.png|thumb|Logo used by the Bell Telephone Company of Canada from 1902 to 1922]]\nThe Bell Telephone Company of Canada Ltd. was created by an [[act of Parliament]] on 29 April 1880. Later known as [[Bell Canada]], its charter granted it the right to construct telephone lines alongside all public rights-of-way in Canada. Under a licensing agreement with the US-based [[Bell Telephone Company|American Bell Telephone Company]], Bell also manufactured telephones and telephone equipment, an activity that would be spun off in a separate company that later became Northern Telecom and then [[Nortel Networks]].\n\nIn 1983, all of the Bell Canada group of companies (also known as the \"Bell Group\") were placed under a new holding company, Bell Canada Enterprises Inc. (BCE). This corporate reorganization resulted in Bell Canada and its subsidiaries, including Northern Telecom (later Nortel Networks) and over 80 others, becoming subsidiaries of the new holding company, BCE. Under the new parent, each company was owned directly by BCE, which had the benefit of freeing the manufacturing company, Nortel, and other holdings from the heavily regulated telephone company, Bell Canada. Under a variety of leaders, BCE has embarked on a series of [[Diversification (marketing strategy)|diversifications]], [[Consolidation (business)|consolidations]], and [[Strategic management|corporate strategies]].<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/bell-canada-enterprises-inc/ Bell Canada Enterprises, The Canadian Encyclopedia]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> In 1988, Bell Canada Enterprises was renamed BCE Inc.\n\n===Diversification and expansion===\nIn 1983, [[A. Jean de Grandpr\u00e9]], chairman of Bell Canada, was appointed as the first chairman and [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of BCE.<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/04/29/Bell-Canada-Enterprises-Inc-has-become-the-new-parent/8282420436800/ ''Bell Canada Enterprises Inc. has become the new parent...'', UPI, April 29, 1983].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  The company soon embarked on a major diversification into property development, the energy sector, financial services, and other sectors.  Within a few years, it became the first Canadian company to report CAD$1 billion in profits.\n\nWhen [[Jean Monty]] assumed the job of CEO in 1998, he pursued a convergence strategy, attempting to combine both content creation and distribution within BCE, and to take greater advantage of the emerging Internet market. BCE's acquisition in 2000 (and subsequent financing) of overseas carrier [[Teleglobe]] cost billions of dollars. BCE sold Teleglobe two years later; Jean Monty resigned and was succeeded by [[Michael Sabia]] as CEO.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Macklem\n  | first = Katherine\n  | title = Monty quits as BCE CEO\n  | publisher = Maclean's Magazine\n  | date = 2002-05-06\n  | url = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=M1SEC677092\n  | accessdate = 2007-06-29\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/2002/04/25/0425monty.html | work=Forbes | title=BCE Backs Away From The Full Monty | date=2002-04-25 | first=Mark | last=Lewis}}</ref>\n\n===Refocus on core business===\nMichael Sabia refocused BCE on its core telecommunications business, prompting BCE to buy back the 20% share in Bell Canada that it had sold in 1999 to [[Ameritech]] (which was subsequently acquired by [[SBC Corporation]]).<ref>{{cite press release\n |title=BCE to Own 100 per cent of Bell Canada \n |publisher=BCE, Inc. \n |date=2002-06-28 \n |url=http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/bce/2002/6/28/69087.html \n |accessdate=2007-06-29 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921172540/http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/bce/2002/6/28/69087.html \n |archivedate=2007-09-21 \n}}</ref> BCE also spun off operating units that it did not consider to be core to its business, including [[Emergis]] in 2004, and [[CTVglobemedia|Bell Globemedia]] and [[Telesat Canada]] in 2006.\n\nOn February 1, 2006, stating the need to remain competitive, Bell Canada announced job cuts of 3,000 to 4,000 employees by the end of 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bell-canada-cuts-471-ontario-jobs-1.589239|title=Bell Canada cuts 471 Ontario jobs {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn April 28, BCE announced that CEO Michael Sabia was taking a 455% pay increase, his salary being raised from [[Canadian dollar|C$]]1.21 million a year to $6.71 million a year.  The pay included a $1.25 million salary, a $2.2 million bonus that Sabia converted to deferred share units, a long-term incentive payout of $3 million and other compensation, the filing shows. Bell Canada also posted record revenue increases for the previous fiscal year.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nUnder pressure from [[investors]], on October 11, 2006, BCE announced it would be wound down, with its remaining assets converted to an [[income trust]] so its income could be distributed directly to [[shareholders]] through [[dividends]], avoiding [[corporate taxes]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bell-canada-to-convert-to-income-trust-1.580316|title=Bell Canada to convert to income trust {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> The new entity was planned to be named \"Bell Canada Income Fund\". As part of this restructuring, Bell Aliant offered to take Bell Nordiq private, while remaining separate from the new Bell trust.<ref>[http://www.cnw.ca/en/releases/archive/October2006/11/c6730.html BCE to be wound down, Bell Canada to convert to income trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617131549/http://www.cnw.ca/en/releases/archive/October2006/11/c6730.html |date=2008-06-17 }}, BCE press release, October 11, 2006</ref> Due to [[Income trust#Canada|announced changes in taxation law]] by the Canadian federal government, on December 12, 2006, BCE announced it would not proceed with its planned conversion to an income trust.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/bce-dies-bell-lives-as-trust/article18174524/ ''BCE dies Bell lives as trust'', The Globe and Mail, Oct. 12, 2006]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/business/story.html?id=beaeacf6-31e2-40cb-9e5c-66ab290453e2 BCE drops its income-trust plan, Montreal Gazette, December 13, 2011].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> It then started planning a restructuring that would have eliminated the BCE holding company,<ref>{{cite press release\n  | title = Bell announces 2007 business outlook&nbsp;\u2014 Improving revenue and EBITDA growth in 2007 guidance\n  | publisher = BCE, Inc.\n  | date = 2006-12-12\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2006/12/12/74065.html\n  | accessdate = 2007-01-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070127225232/http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2006/12/12/74065.html| archivedate= 27 January 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  | title = United States SEC filing, June 12, 2007, Form 6-K\n  | publisher = Securities and Exchange Commission\n  | date = 2007-06-12\n  | url = http://www.secinfo.com/d16Vm2.uv.htm\n  | accessdate = 2007-06-30\n}}</ref> but this was put on hold when the company began attracting [[takeover]] bids.\n\n===Proposed takeover===\nDue to its stagnant [[share price]], starting in April 2007, BCE was courted for acquisition by pension funds and private equity groups, including a consortium led by the [[Canada Pension Plan]] Investment Board (with [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]] as one of the participants), a consortium led by the [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]] (OTPP), and a consortium that included [[Cerberus Capital Management]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Telus's exit likely to pull down price of BCE bids \n |publisher=Reuters \n |date=2002-06-27 \n |url=http://www.globeinvestor.com/servlet/story/ROC.20070627.2007-06-27T170950Z_01_N27295009_RTRIDST_0_BUSINESS-BCE-BIDS-COL/GIStory/ \n |accessdate=2007-06-29 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927174353/http://www.globeinvestor.com/servlet/story/ROC.20070627.2007-06-27T170950Z_01_N27295009_RTRIDST_0_BUSINESS-BCE-BIDS-COL/GIStory/ \n |archivedate=2007-09-27 \n}}</ref>  On June 30, 2007, BCE accepted a bid of $42.75 per share in cash, for a total valuation of $51.7 billion, from the group led by the OTPP, and including [[Providence Equity Partners]], [[Madison Dearborn Partners]], [[Merrill Lynch]] Global Private Equity, and [[Toronto-Dominion Bank]]. The proposed deal would have been the largest acquisition in Canadian history and the largest [[leveraged buyout]] ever.<ref name=\"CanWest-BCETeachers\">{{cite web\n |title=Teachers win BCE bid \n |publisher=CanWest News service \n |date=2007-06-30 \n |url=http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=86dacb18-6f44-4c27-9c38-27e9e48f247b&k=2695 \n |accessdate=2007-06-30 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206115626/http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=86dacb18-6f44-4c27-9c38-27e9e48f247b&k=2695 \n |archivedate=2007-12-06 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-banks\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Sorkin\n  | first = Andrew Ross\n  | last2 = de la Merced\n  | first2 = Michael J.\n  | title = Banks' Terms Imperil Deal to Buy Out Bell Canada\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | date = 2008-05-19\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/19/business/worldbusiness/19deal.html\n  | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}</ref>\nThe deal was approved by BCE shareholders,<ref>{{cite news\n |title=BCE holders approve giant buyout \n |publisher=Toronto Star \n |date=2007-09-22 \n |url=https://www.thestar.com/printArticle/259285 \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071201110321/http://www.thestar.com/printArticle/259285 \n |archive-date=2007-12-01 \n |accessdate=2007-10-01 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n[[Quebec Superior Court]]<ref name=\"CBC-QSCApproval\">{{cite news\n  | author = CBC News\n  | title = Quebec court OK's BCE takeover, dismisses bondholders' complaints\n  | publisher = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n  | date = 2008-03-07\n  | url = http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2008/03/07/bce-ruling.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-06-20\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080508210334/http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2008/03/07/bce-ruling.html| archivedate= 8 May 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n(whose ruling was overturned by the [[Quebec Court of Appeal]],<ref name=\"NYT-QuebecCourt\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Austen\n  | first = Ian\n  | title = Bell Canada Takeover Is Blocked\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | date = 2008-05-22\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/22/business/worldbusiness/22bce.html\n  | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}</ref> but was later upheld by the [[Supreme Court of Canada]]<ref name=\"CP-SupremeApproval\">{{cite web|last=Beltrame |first=Julian |title=Supreme Court approves BCE deal |publisher=The Canadian Press |date=2008-06-20 |url=http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2008/06/20/5941106-cp.html |accessdate=2008-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20081004235833/http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2008/06/20/5941106-cp.html |archivedate=October 4, 2008 }}</ref>),\nand the CRTC, subject to certain conditions for its corporate governance structure to ensure that Bell remained under Canadian control.<ref name=\"CNW-CRTC-approval\">{{cite web\n  | title = CRTC approves BCE purchase with conditions\n  | publisher = CNW Group\n  | date = 2008-03-27\n  | url = http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/March2008/27/c7841.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-03}}</ref>\n(See ''[[BCE Inc v 1976 Debentureholders]]'' for further information).\n\nDue to the tightening of the [[credit market]] caused by the [[subprime mortgage crisis]], the investment banks financing the deal \u2013 led by [[Citigroup]], [[Deutsche Bank]] and the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] \u2013 started negotiations on May 16, 2008, to revise the terms of their loans with greater interest rates and greater restrictions to protect themselves.<ref name=\"NYT-banks\" /> On July 4, 2008, BCE announced that a final agreement had been reached on the terms of the purchase,<ref name=\"BCE-2008FinalAgreement\">{{cite press release\n  | title = BCE and Purchaser Enter Into Final Agreement Financing and Credit Agreements Signed\n  | publisher = BCE, Inc.\n  | date = 2008-07-04\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/07/04/74793.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-08-07\n}}</ref> with all financing in place, and Michael Sabia left BCE, with [[George A. Cope|George Cope]] assuming the position of CEO on July 11.<ref name=\"2008NewCEO-PR\">{{cite press release\n  | title = George Cope appointed to the boards of directors and as CEO of BCE Inc. and Bell Canada\n  | publisher = BCE\n  | date = 2008-07-11\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/07/11/74806.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-07-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080721042212/http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/07/11/74806.html| archivedate= 21 July 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2008, BCE announced that [[KPMG]] had informed BCE that it would not be able to issue a statement on the solvency of the company after its [[privatization]], one of the required conditions of the buyout. As a result, the purchase was cancelled.<ref name=\"CBC-BuyoutCancelled\">{{cite news\n  | author = CBC News\n  | title = BCE takeover deal dead as fight looms over $1.2B breakup fee\n  | publisher = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n  | date = 2008-12-11\n  | url = http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2008/12/11/bce-takeover.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-01-03 }}</ref><ref name=\"BCE-solvencyTest\">{{cite press release\n  | title = BCE statement regarding privatization transaction\n  | publisher = BCE, Inc.\n  | date = 2008-11-26\n  | url = http://www.bce.ca/en/news/releases/corp/2008/11/26/75050.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-12-03\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Expanding again into mass media===\nWith [[Shaw Communications]] purchasing the [[Global Television Network]], [[Vid\u00e9otron]] launching its wireless telephone network with video content as a key selling point,<ref name=\"CTV-Bell-Bet\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Marlow\n  | first = Iain\n  | title = Bell's Big Bet\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-10\n  | url=  https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bells-big-bet/article1703448/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913134643/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bells-big-bet/article1703448/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and the enormous popularity of wireless and Internet video and other media streams at the [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Vancouver Olympics]],<ref name=\"Bell-Vancouver-Olympics-multimedia\">{{Cite news\n  | last = McNish\n  | first = Jacquie\n  |author2=Paul Waldie\n  | title = Olympic moment turned Bell CEO into champion for mobile media\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-11\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/olympic-moment-turned-bell-ceo-into-champion-for-mobile-media/article1703769/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913134914/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/olympic-moment-turned-bell-ceo-into-champion-for-mobile-media/article1703769/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Bell once again sought to bring a content provider into its portfolio. In September 2010, Bell announced a deal to reacquire full control of the broadcasting properties owned by [[CTVglobemedia]] including the [[CTV Television Network]]. Bell also obtained a 15% interest in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', CTVglobemedia's other major asset, with the remaining 85% owned by the [[The Woodbridge Company|Thomson family]].<ref name=\"CTV-purchase\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Marlow\n  | first = Iain\n  | title = BCE-CTV deal remakes media landscape\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-10\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bce-ctv-deal-remakes-media-landscape/article1702385/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913122024/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/bce-ctv-deal-remakes-media-landscape/article1702385/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nThrough this acquisition, Bell responded to an increasing trend away from traditional cable and satellite delivery channels and towards new [[digital distribution|distribution]] methods over the Internet and wireless networks.<ref name=\"CTV-purchase-analysis\">{{Cite news\n  | last = DeCloet\n  | first = Derek\n  | title = The new convergence: A lot like the old version but much, much cheaper\n  | publisher = The Globe and Mail\n  | date = 2010-09-10\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/commentary/derek-decloet/the-new-convergence-a-lot-like-the-old-version-but-much-much-cheaper/article1702799/\n  | accessdate = 2010-09-11\n  | location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100913120117/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/commentary/derek-decloet/the-new-convergence-a-lot-like-the-old-version-but-much-much-cheaper/article1702799/| archivedate= 13 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nThe CRTC approved the transaction in March 2011.<ref name=\"CRTC-approval\">{{cite web\n |author=Canadian Press \n |title=CRTC approves BCE's purchase of CTVglobemedia \n |publisher=CTV.ca \n |date=2011-03-07 \n |url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20110307/crtc-approves-ctvglobemedia-purchase-by-bce-110307/ \n |accessdate=2011-05-23 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629044310/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20110307/crtc-approves-ctvglobemedia-purchase-by-bce-110307/ \n |archivedate=29 June 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, BCE announced that it had entered an agreement to acquire [[Manitoba Telecom Services]] (MTS) in a transaction worth $3.9 billion. The deal has been approved by both companies' shareholders and [[boards of directors]], and is expected to close in late 2016 or early 2017 pending regulatory approval from the [[Competition Bureau]] and other agencies.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hardy|first1=Ian|title=BCE to acquire MTS for $3.9 billion, plans to divest one-third of the postpaid subscribers to Telus|url=http://mobilesyrup.com/2016/05/02/bce-to-acquire-mts-for-3-9-billion-plans-to-divest-one-third-of-the-postpaid-subscribers-to-telus/|publisher=MobileSyrup|accessdate=May 2, 2016|date=May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Major subsidiaries==\nAs of 2016, BCE Inc. has three main subsidiaries: [[Bell Canada]], [[Bell Mobility]], and [[Bell Media]], comprising over 80% of BCE's revenue.<ref name=\"BCE-AR-2015\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.bce.ca/investors/AR-2015/2015-bce-annual-report.pdf\n | title = BCE INC. 2015 ANNUAL REPORT\n | author = BCE Inc.\n | publisher = BCE Inc.\n | access-date = 2016-03-21\n }}</ref> [[Bell Aliant]] was a subsidiary company formed in 1999 from the merger of the four BCE-controlled telephone companies serving Canada's [[Atlantic Canada|Atlantic provinces]]. In 2016, the operations of Bell Aliant were consolidated into those of Bell Canada.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/eng/cht143.pdf CRTC Ownership structure 2015].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Bell Canada===\n{{main|Bell Canada}}\n[[File:Campus Bell in Montreal 1.jpg|thumb|[[Bell Canada]] headquarters in [[Montreal]]. The [[telecommunication]]s company is a subsidiary of BCE Inc.]]\nBell Canada formed the primary historic core of the company in central, Atlantic, and northern Canada. \n* Bell Aliant\n* Distribution (Ontario, Quebec, Atlantic) \u2013 Bell Canada, Cablevision du Nord de Quebec Inc. \n* Bell MTS\n* Bell TV \u2013 Bell ExpressVu Limited Partnership\n\n===Bell Media===\n{{main|Bell Media}}\n[[File:299queenstreetwesttoronto.JPG|thumb|[[Bell Media]] headquarters at [[299 Queen Street West]] in Toronto. The company is BCE's [[mass media]] subsidiary.]]\n[[Bell Media]] is the BCE broadcast and media subsidiary. In 2000, BCE bought the [[CTV Television Network]] for $2.3 billion. The company combined CTV with its holdings in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' newspaper to form Bell Globemedia, with BCE owning 70% and [[Thomson Corporation|Thomson Newspapers]] and Woodbridge Co. Ltd. the remainder.  In 2005, BCE sold its controlling interest in Bell Globemedia for $183 million to Woodbridge, [[Torstar]], and the [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]], with BCE retaining a 20% stake.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bce-to-buy-ctv-for-1-3b-1.888285 ''BCE to buy CTV for $1.3B'', CBC.ca, September 10, 2010].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=886a24ee-5c68-4d17-864b-cdef43fe3324 ''BCE sells most of CTV and the Globe'', National Post, December 3, 2011].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> The company was subsequently renamed CTVglobemedia. In 2007, it acquired most assets of [[CHUM Limited]]. In 2010 BCE bought out the other owners, acquiring CTV's specialty television, digital media, conventional TV and radio broadcasting platforms.<ref>[http://www.ctvnews.ca/bell-canada-parent-bce-buys-ctv-inc-for-1-3b-1.551533 ''Bell Canada parent BCE buys CTV Inc. for $1.3B'', CTV.ca, September 10, 2010].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  In August 2015, BCE sold its remaining 15% stake in the Globe and Mail to Woodbridge.<ref>[http://ca.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idCAKCN0QJ2AJ20150814 Thomson family's Woodbridge buys full control of Globe and Mail, Reuters Canada, August 14, 2015].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  Bell Media's subsidiaries:\n{{col div}}\n* Bell Media TV\n* Bell Media TV \u2013 Sports Specialty Services\n* Bell Media TV \u2013 Specialty Services (other than Sports)\n* Bell Media Radio\n* Bell Media Astral \u2013 Radio, TV, & Specialty Services\n{{col div end}}\n==Other holdings==\nBelow is partial list of the holdings of the BCE conglomerate.\n\n===Montreal Canadiens===\nIn 2009, BCE partnered with the Molson family in acquiring the [[Montreal Canadiens]] Hockey Club and the [[Bell Centre]].  The $575 million purchase was termed \"the richest deal in NHL history\"; BCE's share was reported to be $40 million.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/1220/nhl-valuations-10-geoff-molson-montreal-canadiens-thin-ice.html ''Oh Canadiens: Inside The Richest Deal In NHL History'', Forbes Magazine, 12/02/2010].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment===\nIn 2011, together with [[Rogers Communications]] and Kilmer Sports (holding company of [[Larry Tanenbaum]]), BCE acquired [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]], owner of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] professional hockey team.  BCE's interest is held in partnership with Rogers Communications through the holding company 8047286 Canada Inc., 50% owned by Rogers and 50% by BCE holding company 7680147 Canada Inc., which is in turn 74.67% owned by BCE and 25.33% by BCE Master Trust Fund (investment fund of Bell's pension plan).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/892971/bell-acquires-ownership-position-in-maple-leaf-sports-and-entertainment-mlse|title=Bell acquires ownership position in Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment \u2013 MLSE|author=BCE Inc.|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKilmer Sports and BCE also co-own the [[Toronto Argonauts]], a team the companies purchased in 2015; BCE and Kilmer each own 50% of the team.<ref name=bellannualreport>{{cite web|url=http://www.bce.ca/investors/AR-2015/2015-bce-annual-report.pdf|title=Leading the way in communications|year=2016|accessdate=2016-03-30|publisher=BCE Inc.}}</ref>\n\n==Past holdings==\n===BCE Development===\nBCE Development was founded as '''Daon Development''' by Vancouver-based developer [[Jack Poole]] in 1964. In the mid-1970s, Daon became known for expanding aggressively in the United States. The company first entered the American market in 1976 and nearly quadrupled its total assets to $1.67 billion in four years.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1985-02-03/realestate/re-13512_1_bell-canada ''Bell Canada to Acquire Daon Development Co. : Seeks Controlling Interest in Firm Whose Lightning Rise Ended With the Recession'', LA Times, February 3, 1985].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  It borrowed heavily to finance deals for premium office space and condominium conversions.  By 1981, the company had assets worth more than $2 billion. When interest rates soared, however, Daon was caught overextended, could not meet its debt payments, and was forced into a major restructuring with its bankers. In 1985, BCE acquired 68% of Daon from its creditors and changed its name to BCE Development Corporation in February 1986. In March 1986, it agreed to acquire US$1 billion of commercial real estate from the American subsidiary of the Oxford Development Group Ltd., more than doubling BCED's portfolio. BCE stated its goal was to convert from a land developer to a developer of prime commercial properties.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/03/14/business/business-people-chairman-rebuilding-former-daon-corp.html ''Chairman rebuilding former Daon Corp.'', NY Times, March 14, 1986].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\nIn July 1990, BCE Inc. sold 50% ownership in BCE Development to Carena Developments  Ltd. (controlled by the [[Edper Investments|Toronto branch of the Bronfman family]]).  BCED was renamed Brookfield Development Inc. (now [[Brookfield Asset Management]]) followed in 1994 by the remaining 50%.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-07-03/business/9002230660_1_firm-canadian-changed ''BCE Development Changes Its Name'', Chicago Tribune, July 3, 1990].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2690500032.html Brookfield Properties Corporation, Encyclopedia.com].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://brookfieldofficeproperties.com/_Global/25/img/content/Files/Timeline/Brookfield%20Office%20Properties%20History%20revised%201.11.pdf Brookfield Office Properties history].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Montreal Trust===\nIn March 1989, BCE bought a 64% stake in [[Montreal Trust]] from [[Power Financial]] for $547-million.  The diversification was considered a \"natural evolution\" due to BCE's long-standing interest in financial services, its familiarity in selling services to the public, and its in-house money management operations.  In 1993, BCE sold Montreal Trust to [[Scotiabank]] for about $290-million, taking a substantial loss.<ref>[http://business.financialpost.com/news/fp-street/rogers-bank-plans-lessons-from-bce ''Rogers bank plans: Lessons from BCE'', Financial Post, September 7, 2011].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Nortel Networks===\n[[File:BellPayPhone3.jpg|thumb|upright|A Bell [[Nortel payphones#Millennium|Nortel Millennium]] payphone, introduced in the 1990s. Nortel was a BCE subsidiary from 1983 to 2000.]] \nWhen BCE was created in 1983, [[Northern Telecom]] was transferred from a subsidiary of CRTC-regulated Bell Canada to a non-regulated subsidiary of BCE. In 1998, with Nortel's acquisition of [[Bay Networks]], the company's name was changed to Nortel Networks. As a consequence of the stock transaction used to purchase Bay Networks, BCE's holding was diluted to a minority stake. In 2000, BCE [[spun out]] Nortel, distributing its stock in Nortel to its shareholders. Nortel's share price collapsed with the dot-com crash of 2000 and combined with a mishandling of a subsequent accounting investigation, the company never fully recovered. It was liquidated in 2009.<ref>[http://www.canadianbusiness.com/technology-news/nortel-collapse-of-a-giant/ ''Nortel \u2013 Collapse of a giant'', Canadian Business, January 14, 2009].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref><ref>[http://business.financialpost.com/executive/leadership/lessons-from-nortel-acquisitions-spree-bad-management-calls-led-to-tech-giants-fall-study-says?__lsa=2d67-e92b Lessons from Nortel: Acquisitions spree, bad management calls led to tech giant\u2019s fall, study says, Financial Post, March 17, 2014].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Teleglobe Inc.===\nIn 1987, BCE purchased a 30% stake in [[Memotec Data Incorporated|Memotec Data Corporation]] for $196 million.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AIaZOlcgG28C&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=BCE+acquires+memotec&source=bl&ots=fy-jSQ0pBn&sig=0v3nvWA-GEBcea0yR3MfdlZ3nPk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-5qCmq63LAhVEzGMKHWHyAuYQ6AEIJDAC#v=onepage&q=BCE%20acquires%20memotec&f=false Babe, Robert E.  Telecommunications in Canada: Technology, Industry, and Government. University of Toronto Press, 1990.  Page 30.] {{ISBN|0802067387}}.  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> When Memotec purchased international telecommunications carrier Teleglobe Canada from the Canadian government in 1987, the company was renamed Teleglobe Inc. In March 2000, BCE announced the purchase of the Teleglobe shares it did not own for $9.65 billion.<ref>[http://www.itworldcanada.com/article/bce-goes-international-with-teleglobe/33884 ''BCE goes International with Teleglobe'', IT Canada, March 9, 2000].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> In April 2002, BCE announced it was cutting off long-term funding of Teleglobe, would give up on the company, and take a charge of up to $8.5 billion.<ref>[http://www.lightreading.com/bce-sells-last-of-teleglobe/d/d-id/587290 ''BCE sells last of Teleglobe'', Light Reading, 1/2/2003].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref> In 2005, Teleglobe was sold to the [[Tata Group]] and is now known as [[VSNL International Canada]]. In September 2002, it sold its voice and data business for $197 million.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/teleglobe-sells-voice-and-data-business-1.335698 Teleglobe sells voice and data business, CBC, September 19, 2002].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n===Telesat Canada===\nIn 1970, Bell Canada acquired a minority interest in satellite telecommunications carrier [[Telesat Canada]]. In 1998, BCE raised its stake to 100% at a cost of $158 million for the 42% of shares it did not already own.<ref>[http://www.joc.com/maritime-news/canadas-bce-sell-stake-british-firm_19980513.html ''Canada's BCE sells stake in British Firm'',  Journal of Commerce, May 13, 1998].  Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>  In December 2006, BCE announced the sale of Telesat to [[Loral Space & Communications]] and the [[Public Sector Pension Investment Board]] for CAD$3.28 billion.\n\n===TransCanada Pipelines===\nIn 1983, BCE acquired a controlling 42% stake in [[TransCanada PipeLines Limited]] (TCPL). In 1990, it announced its departure from the energy sector and sold its stake in TCPL for $1.1 billion.<ref>[http://www.referenceforbusiness.com/history2/87/BCE-Inc.html#ixzz42BF1AMZ0 BCE Inc. \u2013 Company Profile, Reference for Business]. Retrieved 2016-03-06</ref>\n\n== Corporate governance ==\nBCE Inc.\u2019s ISS Governance QualityScore as of December 3, 2019 is 2.  The pillar scores are Audit: 1; Board: 3; Shareholder Rights: 3; Compensation: 3. \n\nCorporate governance scores are provided to [[Yahoo Finance]] by [[Institutional Shareholder Services]] (ISS).  Scores denote a [https://www.wisegeek.com/what-is-a-decile-rank.htm decile rank] relative to index or region. A decile score of 1 denotes the lowest governance risk, while a score of 10 denotes the highest governance risk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/BCE/profile/|title=BCE, Inc. (BCE) Company Profile & Facts - Yahoo Finance|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\n=== Board of directors ===\nAs of March 2020, the current [[board of directors]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce.ca/about-bce/leadership-team/board-members|title=Board Members {{!}} BCE Inc.|website=www.bce.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> are:  Barry K. Allen, Mirko Bibic, Sophie Brochu, Robert E. Brown, David F. Denison, Robert P. Dexter, Ian Greenberg, Katherine Lee, Monique F. Leroux, Calin Rovinescu, Karen Sheriff, Robert C. Simmonds, and Paul R. Weiss. \n\nSince inception, BCE has had ''five'' [[CEO]]s:{{col div}}\n*[[A. Jean de Grandpr\u00e9]]: 1983\u20131988\n*[[Jean Monty]]: 1988\u20132002\n*[[Michael Sabia]]: 2002\u20132008\n*[[George A. Cope]]: 2008\u20132020\n*[[Mirko Bibic]]: Current{{col div end}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|http://www.bce.ca}}\n\n{{Bell Canada Enterprises}}\n{{Bell Media}}\n{{Morningstar National Bank Qu\u00e9bec Index}}<!--cat sort position-->\n{{S&P/TSX 60}}<!--cat sort position-->\n\n[[Category:Companies acquired by Bell Canada Enterprises| 01]]\n[[Category:Bell Canada|.01]]\n[[Category:Bell System]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Holding companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Information technology companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Media companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Canada]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Corporate spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Canadian companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Holding companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1983]]\